aVGerman magazine depicts Trump giving Nazi salute The headline also makes reference to Adolf Hitler\u2019s \u2018Mein Kampf.\u2019\u000a\u000aGerman magazine Stern\u2019s latest edition depicts U.S. President Donald Trump giving a Nazi salute on the cover while draped in the American flag, next to a headline reading \u201cSein Kampf\u201d \u2014 \u201chis struggle\u201d and a reference to Adolf Hitler\u2019s manifesto.\u000a\u000aIn Germany, making a Nazi salute is illegal.\u000a\u000aThe cover story about \u201cneo-Nazis, Ku Klux Klan, racism\u201d and \u201chow Trump stokes hate in America\u201d discusses Trump\u2019s handling of the violence in Charlottesville, Virginia earlier this month when a woman was killed during a white nationalist rally when a car rammed into a crowd of counterprotesters.\u000a\u000a"His fight" a play title of Hilter's book 'mein kampf' \u2013 German magazine Stern features Trump. pic.twitter.com/QivSEcyAvu \u2014 Vocal Europe (@thevocaleurope) August 23, 2017\u000a\u000aTrump\u2019s initial statement reacting to 32-year-old Heather Heyer\u2019s death was criticized by Democrats as well as a number of Republicans for not explicitly denouncing white supremacists. He came under fire again days later, when he said there was blame on \u201cboth sides.\u201d\u000a\u000aIn Germany, Chancellor Angela Merkel denounced the events in Charlottesville as \u201cracist,\u201d \u201chorrifying\u201d and \u201cevil,\u201d while her main rival in the September election, Martin Schulz, blasted the chancellor for not condemning Trump himself.\u000a\u000a\u201cA German chancellor needs to tell an American president, \u2018It is absolutely unacceptable when you don\u2019t distance yourself clearly from Nazis,\u2019\u201d Schulz said in an interview with Deutschlandfunk radio last week.\u000a\u000aThe center-left Social Democrat candidate for the chancellorship claimed Merkel \u201chas a habit of waiting\u201d when responding to such events.
