aVLondon Mayor Sadiq Khan (left) is due to meet Woody Johnson (right) in his first month in the post | Source images from EPA and Getty Images Sadiq Khan to meet Trump\u2019s man in London London mayor will be among first to visit new US ambassador to the UK.\u000a\u000aLONDON \u2014 London Mayor Sadiq Khan is due to meet the U.S. president\u2019s new ambassador to the U.K. in his first month in the post.\u000a\u000aThe meeting may be an opportunity to mend fences after Donald Trump attacked the mayor in the aftermath of a terror attack in London in June, in which 8 people died and 48 were injured.\u000a\u000aWoody Johnson, the New York billionaire who begins the plum diplomatic posting next week, already has a diary slot \u201cnot too far in the future\u201d with Khan, an official close to the planning of the meeting told POLITICO.\u000a\u000aFollowing the London Bridge terror attack, Trump criticized Khan for his response. \u201cAt least 7 dead and 48 wounded in terror attack and Mayor of London says there is \u2018no reason to be alarmed!\u2019\u201d Trump tweeted. When the mayor\u2019s office pointed out that Trump had misquoted the London mayor, Trump accused Khan of making a \u201cpathetic excuse.\u201d\u000a\u000aKhan has said a state visit to the U.K. \u2014 offered by Prime Minister Theresa May and accepted by Trump \u2014 should not go ahead.\u000a\u000aBut a spokeswoman for the mayor told POLITICO they were looking forward to a \u201cconstructive relationship\u201d with the new ambassador, as they had done with the former envoy and the charge d\u2019affaires (the acting ambassador).\u000a\u000aIt is standard practice for an ambassador to meet national and senior local leaders when they arrive in a capital, but the encounter between Johnson and Khan will be closely watched given Trump\u2019s outspoken tweets.\u000a\u000aTrump\u2019s man\u000a\u000aJohnson, who owns the New York Jets American football team and is worth $4.2 billion, according to Bloomberg, is due to arrive in London this week, with Tuesday his first official day on the job. (The Jets visited London for a game at Wembley against the Miami Dolphins last year. According to the New York Times, the Jets took their own toilet paper rather than use \u201cthe thinner version used in England.\u201d)\u000a\u000a\u201cClearly he is a personality and with his character, he will have access. He is not a boring person\u201d \u2014 U.K. minister\u000a\u000aThe heir to the Johnson & Johnson pharma company fortune will move into the sumptuous Regent\u2019s Park mansion Winfield House with his wife Suzanne and their two young sons. The neo-Georgian mansion, which at 12 acres has the second largest private garden in central London after Buckingham Palace, was used by the RAF during World War II but was sold to America for a token $1 at the end of the conflict.\u000a\u000aThe 71-year-old started as a supporter of Jeb Bush in the 2016 race for the Republican presidential nomination, but was one of the first major traditional Republican donors to switch his allegiance to Trump.\u000a\u000aJacob Parakilas, deputy leader of the U.S. and the Americas program at the think tank Chatham House, said the \u201cflip side\u201d of a political appointee, as opposed to a career diplomat, was that purely political appointments tended to have a direct line to the White House.\u000a\u000aOne U.K. minister said on condition of anonymity: \u201cClearly he is a personality and with his character, he will have access. He is not a boring person.\u201d\u000a\u000aNigel Farage, the former U.K. Independence Party leader, who Trump suggested would make a great U.K. ambassador to Washington \u2014 a suggestion that received a frosty reception in Downing Street \u2014 met Johnson at a Republican convention.\u000a\u000a\u201cHe comes from a very different background to what one would expect from a diplomat. But I think he is a very committed Anglophile and he wants to see the kind of relationships between our two countries that I have wanted to see for years. I am very positive about it,\u201d Farage said. \u201cI think he is a good chap and I wish him well.\u201d\u000a\u000aTrade deal\u000a\u000aJohnson arrives in London at a critical crossroads for the \u201cspecial relationship\u201d between the U.K. and the U.S., as Britain hopes to forge a new free-trade deal across the Atlantic once it has left the EU.\u000a\u000aJohnson arrives at a \u201csmoothly running embassy,\u201d according to one member of the government.\u000a\u000aSarah Elliott, chairperson of Republicans Overseas U.K., said it was an exciting time to get a fresh perspective and a new person in the role. \u201cThe U.K. and the U.S. are looking at growing that special relationship and looking towards a U.K.-U.S. free-trade deal.\u201d\u000a\u000aBut the British minister downplayed any imminent role for Johnson in trade talks, claiming a deal is \u201cyears off.\u201d\u000a\u000aA good deputy\u000a\u000aJohnson arrives at a \u201csmoothly running embassy,\u201d according to one member of the government.\u000a\u000aLew Lukens, who has been the acting ambassador since the departure of outgoing ambassador Matthew Barzun, has been seen as a \u201cvery good deputy\u201d by the U.K. government, according to one minister.\u000a\u000aParakilas said that when there was a political appointment, \u201ccomplex diplomacy\u201d and \u201cthe management of the sensitive political intelligence relationship\u201d tended to be left to the experienced deputy.\u000a\u000a\u201cThey can be a close adviser to the ambassador and hopefully prevent them from getting themselves and their broad political alignment into trouble, if possible,\u201d Parakilas added.
