aVA Muslim supporter of German Chancellor Angela Merkel attends an electoral meeting on August 14, 2017 in Siegen, ahead of the September general elections | Oliver Berg/AFP via Getty Images Euro-press review How integrated are German Muslims? Also in the news: falling UK migrant rates, Turkey\u2019s \u2018Orwellian\u2019 descent, and more on the Catalonian attacks.\u000a\u000aGermany\u000a\u000aA Bertelsmann Foundation survey that detailed the integration of Germany\u2019s Muslims made a few ripples in the press. The left-leaning Süddeutsche Zeitung led with \u201cTolerance and religion: Most Germans accept Muslims.\u201d Right-leaning Die Welt was skeptical. It published an opinion piece on its front page suggesting that the report was \u201cdeceptive,\u201d since a majority of the same \u201cintegrated\u201d Turks helped Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan consolidate his power in a constitutional referendum in April. \u201cAre these Turks connected to Germany in any way? Even if they are, their behavior is evidence of an understanding of democracy that does not correspond to the Western world \u2014 to be polite.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe Frankfurter Allgemeine led with a story about data protection. Interior Minister Thomas de Maizière defended new security measures like facial recognition software, saying they helped the search for hardened criminals. It also wrote about reported squabbling among the Social Democrats, the Left party and the Greens over a possible coalition after the German election on September 24.\u000a\u000aUK\u000a\u000aThe Office of National Statistics migration report yesterday indicated that an exodus of EU citizens, primarily Eastern Europeans, has already started as net migration was down by 81,000 to 246,000, the lowest since 2014. More problematically for the government, the numbers also revealed only 4,600 international students overstayed their visas in the U.K. last year. When she was home secretary, Prime Minister Theresa May launched a crackdown on international students claiming that more than 100,000 were gaming the system to stay in Britain by attending bogus universities and earning fraudulent degrees. \u201cTheresa May under fire as student visa myth exposed,\u201d led the left-leaning Guardian. Defending the government the tabloid Daily Express led with \u201cMigration slows after EU exit vote: But breaking from Brussels is only way to fully control our borders.\u201d The Financial Times reported: \u201cEmployers seek clarity on EU citizen rights as migration falls.\u201d\u000a\u000aFrance\u000a\u000a\u201cFrench economic recovery confirmed,\u201d Le Monde reported. It also had a story on Hungary, \u201cthe den for the global far right.\u201d Le Figaro lent most of its front page to covering Turkey, with the headline: \u201c[President] Erdo\u011fan imposes his police state in Turkey.\u201d The paper also wrote a editorial titled \u201cOrwell in Istanbul,\u201d in which it commented on Turkey\u2019s transition from a democratic to an \u201cIslamo-Orwellian\u201d state.\u000a\u000aHere\u2019s an excerpt: \u201cThis autocratic drift cannot just be measured in the police stations, the courts and the prisons, which have been largely purged. It can also be read in the streets, schools, in every space where civil society tries to breathe. Textbooks are redacted. The notion of Darwinism is banished, but the notion of jihad is introduced.\u201d\u000a\u000aSpain\u000a\u000aAs the dispute over apportioning responsibility for the twin terror attacks in Catalonia between the national and Catalan authorities grew, Catalan paper Ara issued a call for calm: \u201cPolitical discord plays into the favor of the terrorists,\u201d it said. La Vanguardia reported that Abdelbaki Es Satty, the suspected leader of the terror cell, tried to recruit people during his time in Belgium last year. El Mundo reported that Belgian authorities told Catalan police that Es Satty wanted to go to Barcelona, possibly to conduct an attack.
