aV\u201cStrange statement by Bob Corker considering that he is constantly asking me whether or not he should run again in '18. Tennessee not happy!\u201d President Donald Trump wrote. | Olivier Douliery/Pool/Getty Images) Trump hits back at Corker, says Tennessee 'not happy' with him\u000a\u000aPresident Donald Trump hit back at Sen. Bob Corker\u2019s criticism of him last week, writing on Twitter on Friday morning that it was \u201cstrange comment\u201d and that Corker\u2019s Tennessee constituents are unhappy with their senator.\u000a\u000a\u201cStrange statement by Bob Corker considering that he is constantly asking me whether or not he should run again in '18. Tennessee not happy!\u201d Trump wrote.\u000a\u000aStory Continued Below\u000a\u000aTalking to reporters last week in Tennessee, Corker said that \u201cthe President has not yet been able to demonstrate the stability nor some of the competence that he needs to demonstrate in order to be successful\u201d and that Trump \u201chas not demonstrated that he understands what has made this nation great and what it is today, and he's got to demonstrate the characteristics of a president who understands that.\u201d\u000a\u000aCorker, whose comments came in response to the president\u2019s widely-panned reaction to a deadly white supremacist rally in Charlottesville, Virginia, also said that \u201cradical changes\u201d are necessary to get the White House back on track.\u000a\u000aAsked about those comments at her Thursday press briefing, White House press secretary Sarah Huckabee Sanders said, \u201cI think that's a ridiculous and outrageous claim and doesn't dignify a response from this podium.\u201d\u000a\u000aSign up here for POLITICO Huddle A daily play-by-play of congressional news in your inbox. Email Sign Up By signing up you agree to receive email newsletters or alerts from POLITICO. You can unsubscribe at any time.\u000a\u000aCorker is the latest Republican senator with whom Trump has publicly feuded. In recent weeks, the president has targeted Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) as well as John McCain (R-Ariz.) and Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) over frustration with the Senate\u2019s inability to pass legislation to repeal and replace Obamacare, criticism of Trump's Charlottesville response and overall criticism of his administration thus far.\u000a\u000aCorker's office did not immediately respond to a request for comment on Friday.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAuthors:
