aVGerman Chancellor Angela Merkel | Adam Berry/Getty Images Merkel: \u2018For America to be great, it cannot just care about itself\u2019 German chancellor criticized US president\u2019s \u2018America first\u2019 policy and said calls to increase defense spending predate Trump.\u000a\u000aAngela Merkel said part of the reason why Donald Trump was elected was because of voters\u2019 frustration with the U.S.\u2019s involvement in overseas conflicts and a desire to concentrate on domestic issues. But she added that only focusing on internal affairs is not good for the U.S.\u000a\u000a\u201cAmerica cannot be great if it does not concern itself with things outside its borders,\u201d Merkel said during an interview with business newspaper Handelsblatt on Wednesday.\u000a\u000aStill, Merkel also pointed out that Trump won the election democratically. \u201cHe won a tough campaign. No matter my opinion of him, he deserves respect,\u201d she said.\u000a\u000aMerkel has admitted in the past that the two leaders don\u2019t always see eye-to-eye on matters such as trade and climate change.\u000a\u000aWhen Trump announced, for example, that he would withdraw the U.S. from the Paris climate deal, Merkel called the decision \u201cextremely regrettable\u201d but also stressed it would not stop the rest of the world from tackling the issue.\u000a\u000aMerkel also on Wednesday reiterated her view that Europe cannot just rely on the U.S. to solve problems and should \u201cformulate its own interests,\u201d which may or may not overlap with those of their ally across the Atlantic.\u000a\u000aTrump has also been critical of Germany\u2019s level of defense spending. Germany\u2019s defense expenditure amounts to 1.2 percent of its gross domestic product, whereas the NATO target is 2 percent.\u000a\u000aBut Merkel insisted on Wednesday that the push for Germany to spend more on defense started long before Trump.\u000a\u000a\u201c[Former President Barack] Obama told me frequently that it cannot be that we only spend 1.2 percent.\u201d
