aVTop economic adviser Gary Cohn seemed close to resigning from his post in the Trump administration recently. | Alex Wong/Getty Images 45 After Dark: The Long Goodbye edition\u000a\u000aThe Trump White House seems to be a bit like the Hotel California: You can check in, but it\u2019s awfully hard to leave.\u000a\u000aTop economic adviser Gary Cohn seemed close to resigning \u2014 he\u2019d prepped a letter and his wife encouraged him to leave his post, POLITICO\u2019s Josh Dawsey and Ben White report. After a last minute trip to Bedminster to speak with President Donald Trump, though, no resignation came.\u000a\u000aStory Continued Below\u000a\u000aCohn\u2019s not alone.\u000a\u000a\u201cA number of senior administration officials have offered to leave or privately told confidants they might, only to be told to stay \u2014 or decide to stay on their own. Some were pushed out, or claimed to have resigned after they were pushed out, while one \u2014 former press secretary Sean Spicer \u2014 publicly quit only to stick around in the building with no clear duties, and after facing months of rumors about his demise.\u201d\u000a\u000aAmong those still poking around: Spicer and former chief of staff Reince Priebus, whose employment officially ends at the end of the month. Spicer\u2019s case is more curious: He\u2019s been out of his post for five weeks, but is still on the payroll as he searches for his next gig.\u000a\u000aThe most reliable politics newsletter. Sign up for POLITICO Playbook and get the latest news, every morning \u2014 in your inbox. Email Sign Up By signing up you agree to receive email newsletters or alerts from POLITICO. You can unsubscribe at any time.\u000a\u000aElsewhere in President Trump\u2019s orbit:\u000a\u000aHARVEY DANGER: President Trump is facing his first real weather crisis as president as Hurricane Harvey, now a category 4 storm, bears down on Texas.\u000a\u000aBAN OFFICIAL: President Trump has signed a directive making his ban on transgender service members official.\u000a\u000aJOE FREE AND PROSPER: President Trump followed through on his Tuesday foreshadowing and pardoned controversial former Sheriff Joe Arpaio.\u000a\u000aPOMP\u2019S CIRCUMSTANCE: CIA Director Mike Pompeo is keeping a watchful eye on information the CIA has about Russian collusion and has asked the counterintelligence team to report directly to him. (Washington Post)\u000a\u000aA SEB-ERATION: Controversial White House aide Sebastian Gorka, who was closely aligned with Steve Bannon, resigned citing the White House\u2019s drift from the principles of \u201cMake America Great Again.\u201d\u000a\u000aBREIT LINES: Here\u2019s what a week of Steve Bannon being back in charge of conservative news site Breitbart looks like.\u000a\u000aPUT A CORK IN IT: President Trump lashed out at Tennessee Sen. Bob Corker, saying that his home state is \u201cnot happy\u201d with him.\u000a\u000aMNUCH ADO ABOUT NOTHING: Treasury Sec. Steve Mnuchin says he never thought about resigning after President Trump\u2019s post Charlottesville comments.\u000a\u000aThere you have it. You\u2019re caught up on the Trump administration. Happy Friday. Stay safe Texas.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAuthors:
