aVThe U.K. government is publishing another five position papers on aspects of the talks this week | Carl Court/Getty Images Theresa May \u2018confident\u2019 Brexit talks will move to trade in October UK government under pressure from business to settle post-Brexit trade arrangements quickly.\u000a\u000aLONDON \u2014 Prime Minister Theresa May is \u201cconfident\u201d Brexit negotiations will move on to the \u201cnext phase\u201d of discussing Britain\u2019s future trade relationship with the EU by October.\u000a\u000aThe slow pace of the negotiations thus far has raised doubts that European leaders will agree at a Brussels summit in October that \u201csufficient progress\u201d on separation issues such as the U.K.\u2019s financial obligations will have been made by that time. If they don\u2019t, then the talks cannot progress to dealing with a future trade agreement between the U.K. and the EU.\u000a\u000aBut at a briefing for journalists on Monday, the prime minister\u2019s official spokesperson said the U.K. government was \u201cworking at pace\u201d and would be able to \u201cget to that point.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe comments came after Slovenian Prime Minister Miro Cerar, one of the leaders who will make the \u201csufficient progress\u201d decision, said he thought the process would \u201cdefinitely take more time than we expected at the start of the negotiations.\u201d\u000a\u000aIn an interview with the Guardian, he said there were \u201cso many difficult topics on the table,\u201d he did not expect all the issues to be solved according to the schedule.\u000a\u000aBut the prime minister\u2019s official spokesperson said: \u201cWe are confident that we will have made sufficient progress by October to be able to advance talks to the next phase \u2026 that is our aim and we are confident that we are working at pace and we will be able to get to that point.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe U.K. government is publishing another five position papers on aspects of the talks this week, including on how a future trade deal will be enforced and disputes resolved after May set departure from the European Court of Justice (ECJ) as a negotiation red line.\u000a\u000aMay\u2019s spokesperson said the prime minister believed both sides needed to demonstrate a \u201cdynamic and flexible approach to each round of the negotiations.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cI think we are working at pace and David Davis set out at the weekend [in a comment piece in the Sunday Times] that we want to be able to move on to the next stage by European Council in October and that is our aim.\u201d\u000a\u000aShe said the U.K. Brexit team would be talking to their counterparts about it at the next week\u2019s Brexit negotiations round.\u000a\u000a\u201cDExEU [Department for Exiting the European Union] officials and officials in Brussels talk all the time in between negotiation rounds. We obviously haven\u2019t published the papers yet this week, but they are in regular dialogue with each other and you will be able to hear from David Davis next week at the end of the round how that approach is going.\u201d
