aVBERLIN \u2014 Turkey\u2019s President Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan could end up influencing Germany\u2019s election \u2014 just not in the way he might have hoped.\u000a\u000aInadvertently, Erdogan\u2019s appeal to more than 1.2 million German Turks not to vote for either of Germany\u2019s major parties \u2014 or the Greens \u2014 could help strengthen Chancellor Angela Merkel, with whom he has clashed repeatedly in a series of disputes between the two countries.\u000a\u000aWhile the conservative chancellor has never had much support among ethnic Turks, her principal rival Martin Schulz\u2019s Social Democrats (SPD) have traditionally been the community\u2019s political home \u2014 so they will be hit harder if many German Turks heed Erdo\u011fan\u2019s call.\u000a\u000a\u201cIt\u2019s true that Germans with a Turkish background have tended to vote for leftist parties, even though the distinction has not been quite as clear-cut in the last couple of years,\u201d Niels Annen, a German member of parliament and the spokesperson on foreign affairs for the SPD\u2019s Bundestag group, told POLITICO.\u000a\u000aNot every German of Turkish descent will blindly follow Erdo\u011fan\u2019s appeal, Annen said, adding that \u201cin Germany, votes aren\u2019t given out \u2018en bloc,\u2019 and it\u2019s not decided abroad who is voting for whom.\u201d\u000a\u000aHe also said German politicians should think not about party politics when it comes to Erdo\u011fan\u2019s behavior, but about how Germany should respond to repeated attacks from Ankara.\u000a\u000aGrowing tension\u000a\u000aAmong Germany\u2019s 61.5 million eligible voters, the share of a little more than 1.2 million German Turks seems minute at first glance. But such relatively small groups can make a difference. Not only could German voters of Turkish heritage depress the SPD\u2019s share of the vote, they could also have a say in which coalition options are possible after the September 24 parliamentary election.\u000a\u000aMerkel\u2019s conservatives look set to lead the next government but their partners in office could be determined by fine margins, with more parties than ever expected to enter the German parliament this year.\u000a\u000aAgainst this backdrop, and amid growing tension between Berlin and Ankara over the arrests of German human rights activists in Turkey, Erdo\u011fan launched an attack on Merkel\u2019s conservatives, Schulz\u2019s SPD and the Greens last Friday, calling them \u201cenemies of Turkey\u201d and urging his fellow Turks not to vote for them.\u000a\u000aHis intervention caused fury among German politicians, who were further angered a day later when writer Do\u011fan Akhanli, a Turkish-born German citizen who is an outspoken critic of the Turkish president, was arrested in Spain due to a Turkish extradition request to Interpol.\u000a\u000aMerkel shot back at a campaign event that evening, declaring that Germany \u201cwould not allow any kind of interference\u201d in the election and would \u201cnot let anyone, including President Erdo\u011fan, influence the right of our German citizens, whatever their origin, to vote freely.\u201d\u000a\u000aOn Saturday, Foreign Minister Sigmar Gabriel of the SPD struck a similar note, saying Berlin would not tolerate any Turkish meddling in German politics.\u000a\u000aErdo\u011fan responded swiftly, telling Gabriel that he should learn to \u201cknow your limits\u201d while repeating his call to German Turks to \u201cteach [the parties] a lesson in the German election.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe SPD\u2019s Annen said, \u201cGermany must not rise to provocation, but at the same time, Germany also needs to repudiate those attacks with determination \u2014 and that\u2019s what we did.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u2018Papa\u2019 Schmidt\u000a\u000aOver the decades, the SPD built support among Turks living in Germany \u2014 now more than 3.2 million people \u2014 with its image as an advocate for the working class appealing to many inside the community who never felt fully accepted by the core of German society.\u000a\u000a\u201cHelmut Schmidt is still considered the Papa of Turks in Germany,\u201d said Umut Karaka\u015f, the director of Berlin-based polling institute Data 4U, referring to the former SPD chancellor who pushed \u2014 albeit with limited success \u2014 for better integration of Turkish Gastarbeiter, \u201cguest workers,\u201d during his chancellorship from 1974 to 1982.\u000a\u000aDuring the last national election in 2013, almost two-thirds of all eligible German Turks voted for the Social Democrats, compared to the mere 25.7 percent the party scored overall in the election, according to research by Data 4U, which specializes in surveying German Turks and other ethnic minorities.\u000a\u000aAt the same time, Merkel\u2019s conservatives \u2014 who ended up winning the election resoundingly with 41.5 percent of the vote \u2014 only got 7 percent of the German Turkish vote.\u000a\u000aPolitical estrangement\u000a\u000aBut some German Turkish voters became estranged from German political parties long before Erdo\u011fan\u2019s intervention due to a series of events, including the 2016 decision of the German parliament to declare Ottoman-era killings of Armenians in Turkey a genocide, Karaka\u015f said.\u000a\u000aInfluenced by Turkish state media, which is consumed heavily by German Turks, a feeling within the community of being considered second-class citizens in Germany was reinforced over the last couple of years, she said.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe feeling is that as Turks, they were never really treated on an equal footing.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe SPD\u2019s Annen agreed that \u2014 independent of the discussion provoked by Erdo\u011fan\u2019s comments \u2014 Germany had to look critically at its integration efforts and become better at involving German Turks in the political process.\u000a\u000a\u201cWe have to signal to our German citizens with a Turkish family background that they are part of our country and society,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000a\u201cThey have their place here, and they should not be impressed by the divisive politics of Mr. Erdo\u011fan.\u201d
