aVAfter displaying unity in the aftermath of the twin terror attacks in Barcelona and Cambrils, the blame game between Madrid and Barcelona resumed | Sergio Barrenechea/AFP via Getty Images euro-press review Catalonia attacks drive wedge between Madrid and Barcelona Also in the news: British migration, the return of Hollande and German diesel.\u000a\u000aSpain\u000a\u000aThe truce didn\u2019t hold.\u000a\u000aAfter displaying unity in the aftermath of the twin terror attacks in Barcelona and Cambrils, the blame game between Madrid and Barcelona resumed on Thursday\u2019s Spanish front pages.\u000a\u000aAnti-Catalan independence press highlighted the revelation Catalan police dismissed Belgian authorities\u2019 concerns that terror cell leader Abdelbaki Es Satty, who was in Belgium last year, posed a threat. El Mundo published an editorial heavily criticizing the regional government for failing to prevent the attacks. The paper blamed Catalan police for not sharing the information received from the Belgians with national intelligence and security forces, and accused Catalonia of having a lax approach to Islamic radicalism. While Es Satty was not allowed to run a mosque in Belgium, \u201che had no problem months later running a mosque in Ripoll,\u201d the paper said, \u201cwhich leads us to ask about the lack of controls in religious centers in our country, and specifically in Catalonia.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cThe Catalan government maintains its plan to hold the illegal referendum,\u201d El País reported.\u000a\u000aUK\u000a\u000aMigration was on the front pages of the British press this morning. A review of official data revealed more people are leaving the U.K. than previously thought, prompting net migration to fall to its lowest point in three years. \u201cMigration figures \u2018far lower than thought.'\u201d led the Telegraph. The Times led with a different story on migration: \u201cEU\u2019s failure over illegal migrants fuels crisis.\u201d The i reported Prime Minister Theresa May had softened her stance on a number of Brexit talking points causing a \u201cbacklash\u201d among her \u201cown officials.\u201d\u000a\u000aFrance\u000a\u000aLe Monde published a special report titled \u201cMigrants in Libyan hell,\u201d detailing allegations of torture and harassment of migrants trying to make their way to Europe from Libya. Both Le Monde and Le Figaro reported on the government\u2019s decision to delay promised cuts to social security contributions to keep in line with France\u2019s deficit reduction targets. \u201cGovernment faces headache from 2018 budget,\u201d Le Figaro wrote. The right-leaning newspaper also issued a withering criticism of former President François Hollande\u2019s decision to return to public life after he made an appearance at the Angoulême Film Festival. In an editorial titled \u201cAn opportunity to shut up,\u201d the paper admonished Hollande for presiding over the unemployment of 600,000 people and a negative trade deficit. Macron\u2019s actions, the paper said, are precisely \u201cwhat his predecessor, imbued with his still catastrophic record, recommends not to do. Action or inaction? The French have chosen. A little modesty, Monsieur Hollande!\u201d\u000a\u000aGermany\u000a\u000aFrankfurter Allgemeine led with a story about Germany\u2019s Environment Minister Barbara Hendricks calling for technical upgrades to diesel cars. Left-leaning Süddeutsche Zeitung also led with a story on diesel cars, reporting that software doesn\u2019t make them cleaner.
