aVU.S. armoured vehicles patrol near the site of a U.S. bombing during an operation against Islamic State (IS) militants in the Achin district of Nangarhar provinc | Noorullah Shirzada/AFP via Getty Images EURO-PRESS REVIEW \u2018Trump cedes to the generals\u2019 Also in today\u2019s papers: Brexit and the law, and more details emerge about Barcelona terror cell.\u000a\u000aGermany\u000a\u000aThe German press primarily covered U.S. President Donald Trump\u2019s decision to continue the long-running war in Afghanistan. Leftist paper Die Tageszeitung superimposed Trump\u2019s head on Sylvester Stallone\u2019s body with the caption \u201cTrumbo.\u201d \u201cTrump reverses Afghanistan policy,\u201d Süddeutsche Zeitung wrote. \u201cTrump\u2019s U-turn in Afghanistan puts NATO countries under pressure,\u201d right-leaning Die Welt said. The paper also published an editorial on the front page titled, \u201cThe confusion of the president.\u201d Frankfurter Allgemeine published an editorial and an opinion piece titled \u201cNow it\u2019s also Trump\u2019s war,\u201d and \u201cAn illusion named Trump,\u201d on its front page along with a story about the troop escalation. \u201cTrump: we\u2019re in Afghanistan to kill terrorists,\u201d was the headline.\u000a\u000aSpain\u000a\u000aMuch of the Spanish press reported on new information about the Ripoll terror cell, suspected of being behind the attacks in Barcelona and Cambrils last week. El País reported Belgian police had been in contact with Spanish authorities regarding Abdelbaki Es Satty, the Ripoll imam police suspect was responsible for radicalizing the attackers. El Mundo reported a judge decided against deporting Es Satty in 2015 after ruling he was not a \u201cthreat to public order.\u201d The center-right paper also reported shrapnel and 500 liters of acetone were stored at the house in Alcanar that exploded, reportedly killing Es Satty. La Vanguardia reported on the news the cell was planning to bomb Barcelona\u2019s famous monuments, including the Sagrada Familia.\u000a\u000aFrance\u000a\u000aLeft-leaning Liberation took its cue from the right-wing protests in the United States over the felling of Confederate statues, leading with \u201cSlavery: France has its ghosts too.\u201d Le Figaro reported on the Macron government\u2019s proposed tax reforms on property and wealth. Le Monde published an editorial on Trump and Afghanistan with the title: \u201cTrump cedes to the generals.\u201d\u000a\u000aUK\u000a\u000aThe Telegraph reported the U.K. \u201cwill be bound by European courts\u201d after Brexit. The Guardian featured a similar story, saying a British position paper on Brexit \u201cleaves open possibility of Europe retaining say on U.K. law.\u201d The Times ran a full-page report titled \u201cEurope under threat,\u201d detailing the surge in migrant arrivals from Libya. \u201cTerror warning on unchecked migrants; Italy accuses EU of abandoning it; Calls for Brussels to police Libyan border,\u201d the paper read.
