aVIt was the Instagram post heard \u2018round the world, its ugly words resounding long after it was hastily deleted and disavowed. Louise Linton, the actress-turned-trophy-wife of Treasury Secretary (and foreclosure billionaire) Steven Mnuchin, achieved a trollish trifecta with a screed directed at a random Instagram user and mother of three that was tacky, mean and self-pitying all at once.\u000a\u000aThe offending post:\u000a\u000aScreenshot of Louise Linton's post and the comment she posted.\u000a\u000aStory Continued Below\u000a\u000aAt the speed of cyberspace, the media and Twitterverse invoked the memory of another politically toxic blonde, Marie Antoinette, the fashion-conscious queen beheaded during the French Revolution. The #hermesscarf and #valentinorockstudheels hashtags in Linton\u2019s caption and the apparently frivolous use of a taxpayer-maintained jet might have been enough to draw the comparison on their own, but her sneering response really brought the comparisons to fever pitch. The Washington Post called it \u201cLouise Linton\u2019s \u2018let them eat cake\u2019 moment.\u201d The Huffington Post agreed: \u201cSteve Mnuchin\u2019s Wife Has A \u2018Let Them Eat Cake\u2019 Moment on Instagram.\u201d Vanity Fair declared: \u201cMnuchin\u2019s Wife Goes Full Marie Antoinette In Instagram Meltdown.\u201d One Instagrammer altered the photo of Linton deplaning to depict Marie Antoinette in \u201csunnies.\u201d (It was later revealed that the \u201cForeclosure Queen\u201d had played a Marie Antoinette reenactor in her most notable screen credit, which Vogue damningly described as \u201cexactly one episode\u201d of CSI: New York.)\u000a\u000aBut I have some objections to this. I literally wrote a book on Marie Antoinette and her role as a fashion icon. And while I don\u2019t have undue sympathy for her, I can\u2019t help feeling that she\u2019s the one being maligned by these comparisons and cake references. That\u2019s right: likening Louise Linton\u2014or Ivanka or Melania\u2014to Marie Antoinette isn\u2019t fair to Marie Antoinette.\u000a\u000aThis isn\u2019t the first time the queen\u2019s ghost has returned to haunt the Trump administration. First lady Melania Trump has made several claims to the title of modern-day Marie Antoinette\u2014for example, by appearing on the cover of a magazine pretending to eat a bowl of jewels, or wearing a $51,500 coat to the G-7 summit. Ivanka Trump has also invited comparisons to the queen. There was the $10,000 Trump-branded bracelet she wore on 60 Minutes (then promoted in a press release), the Chinese sweatshops that produce her clothing line, and the infamous Memorial Day champagne popsicle recipe. \u201cIvanka Has Her \u2018Let Them Eat Cake\u2019 Moment, Recommends Champagne Popsicles to Remember Those Who Died In War,\u201d Reddit reported.\u000a\u000aIn a case of history rhyming, cake itself has played a peculiarly prominent role in Trump\u2019s presidency, from Trump touting the \u201cbeautiful piece of chocolate cake\u201d he shared with Chinese President Xi Jinping at Mar-a-Lago to Tina Fey\u2019s satirical advocacy of \u201csheetcaking\u201d as a lazy, self-indulgent alternative to political activism. Eating cake is still a powerful metaphor for performing privilege.\u000a\u000aOf course, Marie Antoinette never actually said \u201cLet them eat cake.\u201d Scholars believe that the quote (\u201cQu\u2019ils mangent de la brioche\u201d)\u2014which she supposedly uttered after being told that her starving peasants had no bread\u2014is likely attributable to one of her predecessors, or perhaps to the imagination of Jean-Jacques Rousseau, who included the phrase in his autobiography. (Though published in 1782, Rousseau\u2019s Confessions were finished in 1770, four years before Marie Antoinette became queen.) But the legend persists precisely because it so conveniently fits our received notions of the queen\u2019s selfishness and immaturity; maybe she didn\u2019t say it, but she could have. Nero didn\u2019t really fiddle while Rome burned, either, but he was unquestionably cruel (and arguably insane).\u000a\u000aBlessed with beauty, wealth, good taste and good intentions, Marie Antoinette was also extravagant, immature and highly susceptible to flattery. But her most significant failings were entirely beyond her control. Born an archduchess of Austria, she was just 14 when she married the heir to the French throne; naturally, it was an arranged union, contracted for dynastic reasons rather than sentimental ones. Her foreign upbringing (and accent) meant that she was never fully accepted or trusted by the French; her husband\u2019s sexual dysfunction kept her from fulfilling her duty of producing a male heir until 11 years into her marriage.\u000a\u000aBy that time, her public image was already in tatters. When a con artist posed as the queen to extort money from a social-climbing cardinal in an elaborate swindle involving a diamond necklace, it was Marie Antoinette whose reputation suffered, though she was entirely innocent. Many other attacks on her fell under the banner of fake news, concocted by gutter journalists and pamphleteers. There was a cottage industry of lesbian porn featuring the queen and her ladies-in-waiting, which many readers took as fact. Further offenses were added to the list of Marie Antoinette\u2019s transgressions long after her death, in heavily fictionalized histories of the ancien régime.\u000a\u000aThough Marie Antoinette was no angel, she was not the snobbish spendthrift she\u2019s often portrayed to be. In fact, if I were to anoint a modern-day Marie Antoinette, it would be Hillary Clinton, not Louise Linton or Ivanka Trump. Like the doomed queen, Clinton on the campaign trail was perfectly well-qualified and well-meaning, but also flawed and naive. She was prone to self-inflicted damage\u2014like her snobby \u201cbasket of deplorables\u201d comment\u2014yet was ultimately brought down by insurmountable exterior forces, including marital baggage, fake news, perverse conspiracy theories and rampant sexism.\u000a\u000aEvery horror story needs a villain. While it\u2019s vastly reductive to blame the entire French Revolution on one person, it\u2019s human nature to seek out a scapegoat\u2014preferably a female, foreign one who wasn\u2019t very popular in the first place. Today, Marie Antoinette is remembered as an unrepentant clotheshorse; her name remains a byword for sartorial extravagance and profligacy. In truth, her wardrobe expenditures weren\u2019t all that unusual for someone in her position, and the revolution wasn\u2019t fought over fashion. Among other things, it was fought over income inequality, tax reform and government debt, of which the queen\u2019s expensive wardrobe was a highly visible reminder.\u000a\u000aWhich brings us to Louise Linton.\u000a\u000aSome fashion writers have argued that Linton\u2019s crime was her rude response to a critic, not advertising her taste for luxury goods in the first place. After all, who among us doesn\u2019t have a healthy appreciation for a #hermesscarf? But context is everything, and Linton was posting as the wife of a civil servant, taking a taxpayer-funded business trip to tour Fort Knox and discuss tax cuts for the wealthy, in one of the country\u2019s poorest states. (What was she even doing there, anyway?)\u000a\u000aThe problem here is Linton\u2019s shamelessness. The generally well-intentioned Marie Antoinette at least fudged her wardrobe accounts so it looked like she was spending less money than she was during an economic crisis. Linton didn\u2019t just dress in an all-designer outfit for the social media cameras; she covered the post with hashtags, recalling actresses and other \u201cinfluencers\u201d who are paid to promote designer labels. Furthermore, the clothes themselves were elitist clichés: Hermès scarf, Birkin bag, \u201cit\u201d shoes, head-to-toe white. And then there\u2019s the disdain: Before she wrote a word of criticism, Linton betrayed her contempt for middle-class America by making sure everyone knew who had designed her clothes and, by extension, how much they had cost. Instagram noticed: After all, Linton\u2019s tantrum was in response to one of many commenters who found her original post distasteful.\u000a\u000aWhile many of Marie Antoinette\u2019s alleged sins were spurious, today\u2019s \u201clet them eat cake\u201d moments are disturbingly credible, chronicled in real time on television and social media. History will remember that Ivanka Trump really did recommend celebrating a day of remembrance with champagne popsicles, and Louise Linton actually had the gall to tag her designer clothes before calling a stranger \u201cadorably out of touch\u201d for questioning her \u201cself-sacrifice.\u201d\u000a\u000aComparisons to Marie-Antoinette normalize this offensive behavior even as they call it out. They remind us that rich and powerful leaders\u2014even pretty, female ones\u2014have always behaved badly. Indeed, they minimize the actions of the Ivankas, Melanias and Louises of the world, because they come across as hyperbole. We all know how Marie Antoinette\u2019s story ended: in bloody revolution, prison and death by guillotine. We\u2019re not there\u2014at least not yet.\u000a\u000aIf Marie Antoinette were around today, I have no doubt she\u2019d be Instagramming her fashion choices (#bighair, #hoopskirt, #diamondnecklace) and making the occasional clueless gaffe on social media. But viciously, publicly, personally attacking a suburban mom? That takes the cake.\u000a\u000aKimberly Chrisman-Campbell is the author of Fashion Victims: Dress at the Court of Louis XVI and Marie-Antoinette.
