aVSo far in the negotiations over Britain\u2019s departure from the EU, U.K. Brexit Secretary David Davis has seemed less than keen to spend any longer in Brussels than absolutely necessary.\u000a\u000aWhen the talks with his EU counterparts got going in earnest in July, he was back in London before you could say \u201cwhere are your briefing papers, David?\u201d But by dashing for the Eurostar as soon as the talks hit the detailed stuff, London\u2019s Brexit honcho risks missing out on some of the European capital\u2019s summer delights.\u000a\u000aSure, Brussels\u2019 EU quarter in August can resemble the apocalyptic wasteland of Cormac McCarthy\u2019s \u201cThe Road\u201d (with more tourists and less cannibalism), but with another trip sous La Manche to come next week, there\u2019s plenty else to occupy Davis and his team when they aren\u2019t stuck in the Commission\u2019s solemn Berlaymont building.\u000a\u000aHere\u2019s POLITICO\u2019s guide to Brussels for the Brexit negotiator in search of late summer downtime:\u000a\u000aGet pissed\u000a\u000aThat\u2019s in the British sense (drunk) not the American sense (angry, there\u2019s plenty of time for that). BXLBeerFest takes place on August 26-27 and offers a chance to sample some Belgian brews. According to the PR blurb, there\u2019ll be beers from around the world \u201cbecause beer has no borders.\u201d It bloody well will after March 2019!\u000a\u000aSalsa time!\u000a\u000aWarm up for a week of meetings with a party at the Fiesta Latina in the Bois de la Cambre, which will see Latin rhythms until late on August 25-27. It\u2019s the perfect opportunity to sample Brazilian beef and get a taste for a delicacy that will flood supermarket shelves in the U.K. after Brexit \u2014 if negotiators can seal that much-anticipated trade deal with the Mercosur bloc once Britain leaves the EU.\u000a\u000aTake the Tintin tour\u000a\u000aTry to forget all about those nasty Eurocrats and their \u201cTintin and the Brexit plan\u201d poster showing Tintin, Captain Haddock and Snowy in a boat that\u2019s on fire. Instead, admire the Tintin street art on Rue de l\u2019Étuve. Belgium\u2019s most famous literary export can be found searching for his friend Professor Calculus, abducted by both Bordurian and Syldavian secret agents after he invented an ultrasonic weapon both sides wanted to misemploy. (Insert joke about Brexit and mutually assured destruction here, dear reader.)\u000a\u000aStock up on Great British supplies\u000a\u000aWith long meetings and closed restaurants, it\u2019s time to grab some British delicacies from the Marks & Spencer store on Avenue de la Toison d\u2019Or before the chain closes the doors of its sole Belgian outlet in late September. British food supplier Stonemanor is open throughout the summer holiday period, peddling its top-selling wares of Cravendale milk, Walkers crisps (or chips, if you will) and Hovis crumpets to hungry officials. If all else fails, there\u2019s the Simply British Fish and Chips food truck.\u000a\u000aRelive the gory glory days\u000a\u000aA day trip to the Lion\u2019s Mound overlooking the site at which British-led forces saw off Napoleon\u2019s French Imperial Guard in 1815 would be the perfect way to remember that other time the Brits changed the course of European history. (In that muddy field 2 kilometers south of Waterloo \u2014 a mere 17-minute train ride from Brussels \u2014 it was support from the Prussian and Dutch armies that allowed the Duke of Wellington to claim victory, but anyway\u2026) Add to the Eurostar itinerary a quick stop at Lille, home of the Fromelles and Ypres battlefields, for more sobering memories of Europe\u2019s past.\u000a\u000aCulture circuit\u000a\u000aA trip to the 1899 art nouveau Old England department store \u2014 now the Musical Instruments Museum \u2014 should be followed by a tipple of Scottish-made Hendrick\u2019s at the aptly named gin bar Pharmacie Anglaise on Coudenberg 66 \u2014 just what the doctor ordered! Finish with a tour of the Magritte Museum to discover just how surreal working in Brussels can be.\u000a\u000aFind a friend\u000a\u000aTake the chance to spend quality time with lesser known EU officials left holding the fort for the summer \u2014 including the Cypriot Christos Stylianides, who will be the sole commissioner in town until August 27. Count MEPs out, of course, since they\u2019re on holiday until early September. New connections could come in handy when the U.K. is out of the EU club. If things go really well, maybe the Brits could even tag along on a European Commission away day, traditionally held at venues in the Belgian towns of Dinant, Grimbergen or Genval. To quote the organizers of such an event: \u201cAll aboard for a day of team fun.\u201d\u000a\u000aWhich way to the beach?\u000a\u000aWith Brexit officials on both sides of the Channel forced to cancel summer holidays to make way for negotiations, the Belgian seaside town of Ostend offers an opportunity to paddle in the North Sea. British visitors may find the popular location a cross between Margate and Marbella, complete with Ferris wheel, a high-rise beach frontage and seafront casino. It will also almost certainly rain!\u000a\u000aSweat it out\u000a\u000aTake a leaf out of Boris Johnson\u2019s book and celebrate the final official day of summer in Brussels by cycling the Gordelfestival on September 3. Those not up to the full 100 km route can take a turn around the Coloma Castle rose garden or, as one expat guide suggests, \u201cjust sweat it out \u2013 that\u2019s how bonds are formed.\u201d As former U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry said of cycling: \u201cIt\u2019s an endurance sport. So is politics.\u201d
