aVPARIS \u2014 If the spring of 2017 was all about Emmanuel Macron and his rise to power, it was his wife Brigitte who owned the summer.\u000a\u000aFrom a controversy over her official title to extensive coverage of her fashion choices, the 64-year-old emerged as a phenomenon in her own right \u2014 France\u2019s first bona fide \u201cfirst lady.\u201d\u000a\u000aSpeaking to Elle magazine this week in her first major interview since her husband\u2019s election, Brigitte Macron said she would play an \u201cinformal\u201d role at the Elysée presidential palace. \u201cIf my presence ever becomes a complication, I will fade into the background,\u201d she told Elle in comments published on Friday.\u000a\u000aBut while she emphasized discretion, there is little doubt about the importance of the role she will end up playing.\u000a\u000a\u201cShe has no intention of taking a frontline political role, but if she is able to help the president in her way, she will\u201d \u2014 Brigitte Macron\u2019s aide\u000a\u000aA constant and influential presence during the presidential campaign, she also had front-row access when her husband was economy minister, sitting in on meetings and weighing in on staffing decisions. At the Elysée, where she will run a staff of five from an office located one floor below her husband\u2019s, she can continue to act as one of his closest advisers.\u000a\u000aNow that she has stepped fully into the limelight, her role can take on an added dimension \u2014 that of a political asset who can be deployed to deflect attention when the going gets tough for her husband.\u000a\u000aThat\u2019s already happening. While his poll scores tumbled ahead of a vacation in Marseille, she filled the news pages with a controversy about her official role and title that ran for most of the summer, culminating in her big set-piece interview for Elle.\u000a\u000aWith the country\u2019s attention distracted, Macron\u2019s team hammered out the final details of an explosive overhaul of labor rules that is to be pushed through via decree next month.\u000a\u000aThe Macrons\u2019 routine, in which the president steps back so his wife can step forward, may well prove to be a handy template during the tough months to come.\u000a\u000a\u201cShe has no intention of taking a frontline political role, but if she is able to help the president in her way, she will,\u201d said an aide to Brigitte Macron.\u000a\u000aQuasi-royal\u000a\u000aWhen the French public first started to take notice of Brigitte Macron around three years ago, stories focused on the details of her and her husband\u2019s romance.\u000a\u000aThere was fascination, and some incredulity, with a teacher who left a husband with whom she had three children to marry her former student, whom she met when he was 15.\u000a\u000aHer first magazine covers, in which the Macrons were photographed walking on the beach, came at a crucial time in his campaign \u2014 as opponents were circulating rumors about his sexual orientation.\u000a\u000aBut since Macron came to power, the salacious edge to media coverage of the presidential couple has gone. And Brigitte Macron, no longer an object of curiosity, now fascinates as a quasi-royal figure.\u000a\u000aThe summer of Brigitte started in July, when Donald Trump and his wife Melania visited Paris. The U.S. president\u2019s remark about Mrs. Macron\u2019s appearance, that she was in \u201csuch great shape,\u201d prompted outrage about him being ageist and sexist.\u000a\u000aBut it also focused worldwide attention onto Brigitte and the contrast between the French president\u2019s wife, more than two decades her husband\u2019s senior, and the self-effacing Melania Trump.\u000a\u000aBrigitte, friends argued, was a non-conformist, praiseworthy for having defied the idea that rich and powerful men should have much younger wives. She had a long career in education and participated closely in her husband\u2019s political rise. Melania, by contrast, was an extension of her husband, with no political role.\u000a\u000aThe encounter with Trump at the Invalides in Paris was also the moment that the fashion press noticed Brigitte Macron. Her white Louis Vuitton dress \u2014 she has several, in different colors \u2014 prompted dozens of articles about French chic. Brigitte Macron, typically, embraced her role as fashion ambassador.\u000a\u000a\u201cWhenever I travel abroad, I\u2019m constantly being asked about what I am wearing,\u201d she told France Info in July. \u201cIt\u2019s an art, a total art, and I am very happy if I can contribute by bringing some visibility.\u201d\u000a\u000aA few weeks later, high-street fashion brand H&M started selling a T-shirt emblazoned with her first name in pink letters at its flagship Paris store. The shirts sold out within a day, and after restocking the firm decided to extend its one-week \u201cBrigitte\u201d campaign for a month.\u000a\u000aBeyond her fashion choices, however, it was the question of Brigitte Macron\u2019s status within the power structure of the French Republic that gripped France. Despite no formal attempt having been made to enshrine the status of a \u201cfirst lady\u201d in the constitution, an artist launched an online petition opposing the idea.\u000a\u000aSome 250,000 virtual signatures later, the Macrons formally distanced themselves from the idea. However, it\u2019s been a positive for Brigitte Macron, who\u2019s now linked to the words \u201cfirst lady\u201d \u2014 \u201cpremière dame.\u201d\u000a\u000aShe used the issue to underscore, in her interview with Elle, how she would have a more important role than previous first wives because the budget for her staff, previously subsumed into the Elysée\u2019s general expenses, would be made public.\u000a\u000aWhen the presidential couple appeared in Marseille for their brief, supposedly secret, summer holiday, it was Brigitte, not Emmanuel, who was spotted by a bystander. She had gone to say hello to a neighbor.\u000a\u000aSo much for discretion \u2014 and so much the better for the woman who owned the summer of 2017.
