aVJennifer Martinez Young\u2019s 8-year-old daughter, Addison, blitzes through books: Lisa Yee\u2019s DC Super Hero Girls novels, the Rainbow Fairies and Mariella Mystery series. Just starting third grade, she\u2019s reading at almost a sixth-grade level. This year, at Addison\u2019s former elementary school, fifth-graders will read a story she wrote last year, as a model.\u000a\u000aAddison\u2019s mother credits her pre-school, San Antonio\u2019s Pre-K 4 SA North Education Center, for inspiring her love of reading. Addison is still pen pals with Mrs. Ashworth, her preschool teacher. \u201cShe says she taught her so much,\u201d Martinez Young, 37, says.\u000a\u000aIn 2013, Addison was one of the first 700 4-year-olds to enroll in San Antonio\u2019s Pre-K 4 SA program, which provides high-quality, full-day pre-kindergarten for disadvantaged 4-year-olds. It\u2019s the brainchild of former San Antonio Mayor Julián Castro, who went on to serve as President Barack Obama\u2019s secretary of Housing and Urban Development.\u000a\u000aSince then, Pre-K 4 SA has posted impressive results. Its kids start below the national average in cognition, math and literacy, and finish the year above average. Its founders have become evangelists for the idea that early-childhood education is key to giving poor kids an equal chance to succeed in school and life. The goal, says Sarah Baray, Pre-K 4 SA\u2019s CEO, is nothing less than \u201cto change the trajectory of San Antonio in one generation.\u201d\u000a\u000aIt\u2019s an unusual way to transform a city. Often mayors get behind mass transit or downtown redevelopment to improve their cities, not educational play for 4-year-olds. But the need for pre-K is a hotly debated topic around the country. A few cities and states have adopted universal pre-K, while others are building toward it. Texas is not one of them. Castro\u2019s initiative represents an ambitious but controversial example of a city jumping to fill a void left by its state government. \u201cThe best way to make sure a young person gets ahead is to make sure she never gets behind in the first place,\u201d says Castro.\u000a\u000aIf the program succeeds, its backers say, it could transform San Antonio, a fast-growing, majority-Latino city of 1.5 million people that calls itself \u201cMilitary City\u201d because of several large bases it hosts. It could also be a signature résumé line for Castro, whom Hillary Clinton considered as a potential running mate last year, if he decides to pursue a run for office in 2020. Castro, 42, formed a PAC to support federal candidates last week and hasn\u2019t ruled out a run for president.\u000a\u000aPre-K 4 SA\u2019s curriculum is based on decades of research on how younger kids learn\u2014ways that don\u2019t look much like traditional school at all. Pre-K 4 SA kids tend gardens, make art and raise money for charities. They learn through play\u2014 scooping sand into jars, rolling balls down slopes. Teachers ask each of them questions, to turn their play into teachable moments.\u000a\u000aStory Continued Below\u000a\u000aMartinez Young, a stay-at-home mom, and her husband, a part-time insurance agent and student, were so impressed with Addison\u2019s experience in Pre-K 4 SA, they enrolled their younger daughter, Samantha, last year. Martinez Young could have spared herself the 20-minute drive to the North Education Center if she\u2019d enrolled Samantha in the pre-kindergarten program at Addison\u2019s school. But from what she\u2019d seen of it as PTA president, she wasn\u2019t impressed.\u000a\u000a\u201cIt was, \u2018OK, everybody, we\u2019re doing this worksheet now. Color this, glue this,\u2019\u201d says Martinez Young. It looked like regular school to her, with all the kids doing the same thing. Pre-K 4 SA is more \u201chands-on,\u201d Martinez Young says. \u201cI liked the fact they work in the garden. They have their own sense of, \u2018This belongs to me, this is what I\u2019m working on, this is a plant that I\u2019m watering, this is what I\u2019m going to grow.\u2019\u201d The teachers even persuade some of the 4-year-olds (though not all, of course) to eat the vegetables they grew.\u000a\u000aFormer San Antonio mayor Julian Castro stands under a mural at Pre-K 4 SA's north campus with his 8-year old daughter, Carina. Inside, teachers train and set up their classrooms before the rapidly approaching first day of school. | Mark Peterson/Redux Pictures for Politico Magazine\u000a\u000aThe curriculum might sound wholesome and innocent, but the politics around the passage of Pre-K 4 SA were anything but. Castro had to fight conservative critics who felt the city government shouldn\u2019t raise taxes or get involved in education. Castro, who said he was prepared to stake his whole administration on the proposal, didn\u2019t flinch. \u201cCities are often good at asking for a sales tax hike to invest in stadiums, or roads, or an airport, but less so to invest in people directly,\u201d Castro told POLITICO Magazine in a July interview. Castro brought in local business leaders and sweetened the proposal by offering scholarships for middle-class families, grants to private schools and professional development for public-school teachers. In 2012, San Antonio a solid 54 percent of San Antonio voters approved a 1/8-cent tax hike to fund Pre-K 4 SA. The criticism hasn\u2019t entirely abated, however. Half of the 16 school districts that cover parts of the 467-square-mile city chose not to participate in the program. And even those that agreed to partner with Pre-K 4 SA have done so uneasily.\u000a\u000aThe next three years will be crucial for Pre-K 4 SA\u2019s future. In spring 2018, its first alumni will take Texas\u2019 standardized math and reading tests. How the kids do could be key to evaluating whether their carefully chosen pre-school curriculum really gives them a boost in education and life. It will also influence what San Antonio voters do in 2020, when they\u2019ll decide whether to keep the program or kill it.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a***\u000a\u000aJulián Castro launched his first San Antonio City Council campaign while he was still a Harvard Law student, fundraising among his classmates and tacking a map of the district onto his dorm room wall. Elected at age 26 in 2001, he was the city\u2019s youngest-ever councilman. He swept into the mayor\u2019s office on his second try in 2009, winning by a 27-point margin on a platform of job creation and improving early-childhood education. Within a year, a New York Times Magazine profile identified him as a rising talent, quoting Republican political adviser Mark McKinnon, who said Castro had a good chance of becoming the nation\u2019s first Hispanic president.\u000a\u000aImage Teachers stock their classrooms with toys made out of everyday objects students might also find within their homes\u2014encouraging them to play creatively during and after school. Desks and furniture are muted and neutral in hue, so students don't become distracted by color. | Mark Peterson/Redux Pictures for Politico Magazine\u000a\u000aPressed by the city\u2019s two-year election cycle, in 2010 Castro quickly launched an effort called SA 2020, which asked residents what they wanted their community to look like in 10 years. Public forums attracted 700 to 1,200 people. The consensus: San Antonians wanted to target transportation, housing, downtown development, and\u2014most of all\u2014their kids\u2019 low high-school and college graduation rates. Almost 20 percent of San Antonians age 25 and over didn\u2019t have a high-school diploma in 2012, and 75 percent didn\u2019t have a bachelor\u2019s degree, according to the U.S. Census. \u201cHow do we ensure there are better opportunities for folks, because they\u2019re better educated?\u201d Castro tells POLITICO Magazine.\u000a\u000aSo Castro set up the Brainpower Initiative Task Force to choose the best way to help. He asked the heads of San Antonio\u2019s two largest private employers to serve as co-chairs: Charles Butt, founder and CEO of H-E-B, Texas\u2019 largest grocery store chain, and Joe Robles, Jr., a retired Army major-general who was then CEO of USAA, the insurance and financial-services company for veterans.\u000a\u000aButt and Robles looked at research studies on three possible areas of focus: college attainment, help for middle-school kids falling behind, or early-childhood education. The results were clear, they reported: spending on early childhood provided the best return on investment. A high-quality pre-kindergarten program sets up poorer kids to perform at grade level by third grade, the research showed, which increases their chances of graduating from high school.\u000a\u000aAt his State of the City address in March 2012, Castro announced his proposal to put Pre-K 4 SA on the ballot. \u201cI am willing to stake my entire mayoral tenure on the need to invest in these young people,\u201d he said at the time. The potential career risks and rewards for Castro grew stronger that summer, when President Obama chose him as the keynote speaker at the Democratic National Convention\u2014the same speaking slot that introduced Obama to a national audience in 2004.\u000a\u000aTo fund Pre-K 4 SA, Castro turned to the city sales tax. \u201cIt was the first time we ever asked residents to raise the sales tax to invest in people as opposed to things,\u201d Castro says. San Antonio already had a sales tax of 1.875 cents per dollar, which funded the city government, parks, roads and the local bus system. Texas law caps local sales taxes at 2 cents per dollar, leaving San Antonio 1/8 cent of taxing capacity, enough to raise about $32 million a year.\u000a\u000aPre-K 4 SA has centers located in each corner of San Antonio, all near freeway beltways. In all, 2000 lower-income students are taught at the four campuses. | Mark Peterson/Redux Pictures\u000a\u000aCastro\u2019s goal was to do early-childhood education better than Texas\u2019 existing programs. The state funds free half-day pre-kindergarten for low-income kids, English language learners, and kids from military families. School districts use those funds to pay for pre-K classes in their elementary schools, and some were adding local funds to offer full-day pre-K. Other city kids were in the federal Head Start program. But the task force found that 5,700 San Antonio kids\u2014about 30 percent of the city\u2019s population of 4-year-olds, most of them Latino or black, like the city as a whole\u2014were eligible for free pre-K, but were either enrolled in a half-day program or none at all.\u000a\u000aCreating a citywide education program was tough in San Antonio, a sprawling, fast-growing city whose boundaries overlap with 16 independent school districts. (Many districts were founded decades before San Antonio began to annex new territory in the 1940s.) Some districts fall entirely within the city, while some have only a sliver of overlap inside the city limits.\u000a\u000aAfter looking at the status quo, Castro and his advisers decided not to subsidize the schools\u2019 existing programs. \u201cThe quality of their pre-K was very uneven,\u201d he says. \u201cEverybody involved wanted this to be an absolutely top-rate program.\u201d Besides, San Antonio\u2019s two largest school districts, Northside and North East, were too crowded to add more classes. Finally, Castro also wanted to expand pre-K access to reach parents with household incomes above Texas\u2019 cutoff, 185 percent of the poverty line\u2014a project the districts were leery of taking on. In Texas\u2019 system, \u201cthe middle class gets screwed,\u201d he argues. \u201cTons of families, essentially the lower middle class and middle class, can\u2019t afford good pre-K in a private school.\u201d\u000a\u000aCastro\u2019s solution: \u201cexcellent full day pre-K that wasn\u2019t bounded by these district lines.\u201d The city would build four pre-K centers, each enrolling 500 kids a year, on the north, south, east and west sides. Parents could choose the one closest to home or work.\u000a\u000aGetting the tax passed wasn\u2019t easy. \u201cWe were asking people to tax themselves in a state and a community where that\u2019s not necessarily popular,\u201d Castro says. Pre-K 4 SA would teach 2,000 kids a year, about one-tenth of the 4-year-olds in the city. To expand the program\u2019s reach and political support, Castro, the task force and the city manager\u2019s staff also included a $4 million competitive grant program for public, private, parochial and charter schools, and child development centers. They also promised a teacher training initiative that would spread Pre-K 4 SA\u2019s approach to learning around town.\u000a\u000aStudents are off for the summer, but summer food programs at Boys and Girls Clubs across the city serve lunches and offer kids a space to gather, indoors and out. | Mark Peterson/Redux Pictures for Politico Magazine\u000a\u000a\u201cThe biggest thing was promoting a vision of a much more well-educated San Antonio, for the sake of those children, but also for everybody\u2019s sake,\u201d says Castro. With the business community\u2019s help, Castro made the case that Pre-K 4 SA was a workforce development program with a very long-term payoff. (Four-year-olds starting Pre-K 4 SA this fall will be part of San Antonio\u2019s high school classes of 2031.)\u000a\u000a\u201cEveryone would benefit from the better jobs that could be brought in, the higher salaries of the future,\u201d Castro says.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a***\u000a\u000aBefore Sarah Baray became CEO of Pre-K 4 SA in 2016, she was a tenured university professor who studied school improvement and focused on disenfranchised kids. She gave up the security of tenure for her new job because she was excited by her tour of a Pre-K 4 SA center.\u000a\u000a\u201cHere was this program where they\u2019d done it exactly right,\u201d Baray recalls. In every classroom, she says, all the children were focused on hands-on play, experimenting with objects chosen to fit a lesson. No teacher had a desk. Instead, the teachers were all going from child to child, interacting with them one-on-one.\u000a\u000aBaray was familiar with the strategy: Pre-K 4 SA was using early-childhood best practices, with kids learning through well-directed play. She\u2019d just never seen it this well-executed. In her research on school improvement, she was used to seeing schools where bright spots mixed with disengaged teachers and kids doing rote work. \u201cThe kids were very comfortable explaining their learning to me,\u201d she recalls. \u201cThey showed me around the classroom. They were very confident, eager learners.\u201d Some kids in a dramatic play area were pretending to run a restaurant: carrying sticks, rocks, empty food boxes, plastic plates brought from home, a plastic apple. They put on clothes, set tables, and acted as waitresses. Some wrote down letters and words as if writing recipes \u2014 learning literacy as they imagined.\u000a\u000aNow, Baray is in charge of all four Pre-K 4 SA centers, and she\u2019s spreading the word about pre-K best practices across San Antonio. The curriculum comes from HighScope, a Michigan-based early-childhood program that encourages active, participatory learning.\u000a\u000aPre-K 4 SA CEO Sarah Baray (center) in the East campus, surrounded by teachers participating in a training. | Mark Peterson/Redux Pictures for Politico Magazine\u000a\u000aHighScope\u2019s approach is based on the Perry Preschool Project, a 1960s preschool program for low-income kids at Perry Elementary School in Ypsilanti, Michigan. The Perry project was based on child-development research by pioneering psychologists Jerome Bruner and Lev Vygotsky, who found that children learn best through experimental play, with adults stepping in at the right time to help them grasp a new concept. A study checked in with Perry alumni at age 40 and found that they\u2019d been more successful in life than peers who didn\u2019t attend: They were more likely to have graduated from high school, used welfare less, were arrested less, and earned more. Studies by James Heckman, a University of Chicago economics professor and Nobel laureate, back up HighScope-style approaches to pre-school. \u201cA wide range of studies show that disadvantaged children benefit from access to quality early childhood programs\u2014and society benefits from targeted investments in disadvantaged children,\u201d says a summary of Heckman\u2019s findings on his website. \u201cHigher quality programs like Perry Preschool,\u201d it adds, \u201cproduce the highest quality outcomes.\u201d\u000a\u000aPre-K 4 SA launched fast. Castro asked city manager Sheryl Sculley to start the program in September 2013, just 10 months after voters approved the funding. The North and South education centers opened first, the East and West the following year. All are on the edge of the sprawling city, near a beltway of freeways.\u000a\u000aThe centers open at 7:15 a.m. for breakfast. The regular school day ends at 3 p.m., but about 40 percent of the kids stay for an extended day program for children of working parents, which goes to 6 p.m. Many parents say they couldn\u2019t enroll their children in pre-school without the extended day, says Sculley. Pre-K 4 SA is free for 80 percent of the families, who qualify under the Texas law for disadvantaged or military households. The other 20 percent are middle-class families with an income of more than 185 percent of the poverty line\u2014$44,000 for a family of four. They pay tuition based on a sliding scale.\u000a\u000aAll the centers except the North center are in newly consrtructed buildings. The North Education Center is housed in a former Southwest Airlines call center. It\u2019s been gutted to create classrooms with wide interior windows, for classroom observation. Five playgrounds line the building\u2019s façade on two sides. In warm, sunny San Antonio, outdoor education happens throughout the school year.\u000a\u000aThe goal of Pre-K 4 SA is to structure kids\u2019 play by creating an environment full of well-chosen objects, so they can\u2019t help but learn.\u000a\u000a\u201cWhen kids are out in the sandbox, or working in a water tub and pouring from one jar into another, they\u2019re building the foundational understanding for capacity,\u201d says Baray. \u201cLater, a teacher in upper grades can tap into that, saying: \u2018Remember when you were pouring this?\u2019 So they have a foundational understanding that different containers hold different amounts.\u201d In regular day care, or pre-K with a less skilled teacher, says Baray, \u201ckids are doing those same kind of things, but they don\u2019t have the adult near them that can ask the questions that push the thinking, or set up the environment for the next step.\u201d\u000a\u000aPre-K 4 SA\u2019s curriculum also includes social and emotional learning, which teaches lessons such as teamwork, cooperation and self-control. Those lessons will pay off when the kids become teenagers, says Baray. \u201cIf children have not learned to have some control over their response to what\u2019s happening to them, that\u2019s when we see behavior that\u2019s much more problematic, [or] completely out of control.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe north campus playground was carefully designed to be colorful and stimulating; to balance natural elements and man-made structures; and to create an environment that feels exciting but keeps kids safe. Over the years, parents have volunteered to help build it themselves. | Mark Peterson/Redux Pictures for Politico Magazine\u000a\u000aThe North center includes a quiet room, with green-purple-and-blue flags hung from the ceiling to cover the fluorescent lights. \u201cCatch your breath, take your time,\u201d says a message on the wall, written in a dreamy cursive. Here, the pre-schoolers learn yoga and meditation. \u201cThat really helps children with regulating their emotions and behaviors,\u201d says center director Sandy Weser. \u201cBy the time children leave, they\u2019ve learned the importance of breathing: \u2018When I get upset I just breathe, and I calm down, and then I can talk about what I\u2019m upset about.\u2019 \u201d\u000a\u000aThe program also aims to teach kids to be creative citizens. A civic engagement program teaches them about charities. Near Election Day, the kids vote on which nonprofit to support. (Charities that help young children or animals usually win.) Then they fundraise, volunteer or participate in food drives. A field-trip program takes the kids and their families to parks in parts of San Antonio many haven\u2019t seen, where they learn about nature. \u201cIt\u2019s not just about going to see the Alamo\u2014it\u2019s really about understanding their community,\u201d Baray says. Local artists visit the center to teach kids to create art projects they sell at a community auction. Last year\u2019s auction raised more than $4,000.\u000a\u000aEach center has a professional development classroom, where Pre-K 4 SA trains other San Antonio pre-school teachers in its methods. This year, the program is ramping up similar training for kindergarten through third-grade teachers. They\u2019ll instruct them in the \u201cintentional release model,\u201d which transitions kids from learning by play in kindergarten to traditional, desk-based learning by third grade. The goals are to help the elementary schools, and to make sure the Pre-K 4 SA kids\u2019 successes last. \u201cWe don\u2019t want our children to get into the public school setting and then wait for all the other kids to catch up to where they are,\u201d Sculley says.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a***\u000a\u000aPre-K 4 SA\u2019s job is uplift. It\u2019s not universal pre-kindergarten, it\u2019s pre-K for disadvantaged kids. It\u2019s meant to make up for differences at life\u2019s start: poverty, a language barrier. The approach assumes that affluent kids don\u2019t need a boost; their parents will pay for private preschool. It helps some middle-class families, but there\u2019s a limit; at high incomes, the sliding-scale tuition becomes pricier than private preschool. New York City Mayor Bill de Blasio spoke to Castro while putting together his preschool initiative, but he chose to go further than the San Antonio model and offer a universal program, Pre-K For All.\u000a\u000aThe results available so far suggest Pre-K 4 SA is working. At the start and end of the school year, Pre-K 4 SA teachers evaluate their kids according to six national standards for kindergarten readiness. They start the year significantly below the national average on all six. By year\u2019s end, they\u2019re above the national average on math, literacy and cognition, they\u2019ve reached the national average on oral language and social-emotional readiness, and they\u2019ve closed three-fourths of the gap on physical skills such as coordination, balance, playing with a ball and drawing.\u000a\u000aAnd the teachers are being assessed as well. Pre-K 4 SA pays its teachers an average salary of $66,500, compared with the San Antonio area\u2019s average salary of $51,400 for all teachers. Its first round of hires came mostly from San Antonio-area schools, but it\u2019s now recruiting nationally. Mostly, its efforts to attract top-quality teachers are paying off. An outside evaluator has given the teachers high ratings. \u201cOverall, teachers were observed displaying high levels of emotional support and relatively high levels of classroom organization,\u201d reported Edvance Research in its evaluation of Pre-K 4 SA\u2019s third year. Edvance rated the centers\u2019 instructional support as average and improving. Overall, the teachers scored above average compared to national standards for Head Start programs.\u000a\u000aThe exception was Pre-K 4 SA\u2019s East Education Center, which covers a lower-income part of the city. Its teachers got lower scores from Edvance than the other centers. Also, kids at the East and West showed smaller gains than the North and South centers (but better gains than the national average). \u201cThe East center lags a bit in teacher quality compared to the other centers, but they\u2019re still light years above most programs in San Antonio,\u201d Baray asserts. Without data to back that up, she cites her own experience as a researcher and scholarly work that she says \u201csuggests the quality of most pre-K programs is not high enough to improve [kindergarten] readiness.\u201d\u000a\u000aAbove, City Manager Sheryl Sculley framed by the wide interior window of a Pre-K 4 SA classroom. Bottom left, Castro addresses a room of teachers who are about to start the year. Bottom right, teachers decorate balls, soon to be kicked around by energetic 4-year-olds. | Mark Peterson/Redux Pictures for Politico Magazine\u000a\u000aSculley says Pre-K 4 SA has been re-evaluating its East center teachers and teaching assistants. Because teachers in the program aren\u2019t unionized, she notes, teachers are employed at-will, so \u201cwe can move teachers around, and also make adjustments in teacher performance.\u201d The East center\u2019s director retired this summer, and the program plans to conduct a national search for a successor.\u000a\u000aSo far, Pre-K 4 SA doesn\u2019t have data on how kids do once they move on to elementary school. The program\u2019s alumni aren\u2019t quite old enough to take Texas\u2019 standardized tests yet, and San Antonio\u2019s school districts have been loath to share their internal evaluations of students\u2019 progress.\u000a\u000a\u201cCandidly, the districts are a little bit worried about, are we going to show them up?\u201d says Sculley. \u201cThey say, \u2018Well, you\u2019re spending a lot of money per child. Of course your kids are going to perform better.\u2019\u201d It\u2019s the biggest point of contention in Pre-K 4 SA\u2019s complicated relationship with San Antonio\u2019s many school districts.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a***\u000a\u000aRey Madrigal is superintendent of the Harlandale school district, one of eight in the city of San Antonio that partners with Pre-K 4 SA. Harlandale serves 15,000 students across a stretch of San Antonio\u2019s South Side, about 85 percent of them from low-income families. \u201cWe tax our community at the highest rate the state allows,\u201d Madrigal says. \u201cWe have to, to survive.\u201d\u000a\u000aHarlandale started a pre-K program 20 years ago and upgraded it to a full-day program 15 years ago. When voters approved Castro\u2019s brainpower initiative, Harlandale\u2019s pre-K was at capacity. \u201cI had 80 kids at home, who were waiting to be educated,\u201d Madrigal says. \u201cIf I don\u2019t, I\u2019ll spend more money later, in remediation.\u201d\u000a\u000aNow, thanks to its partnership with Pre-K 4 SA, Harlandale has more kids ready for kindergarten, no waiting list for pre-school, and more professional development for its teachers. Pre-K 4 SA sets aside about 80 seats in its classrooms for Harlandale 4-year-olds. In exchange, Pre-K 4 SA gets almost all of the state\u2019s $3,600 per pupil pre-K grant for the kids it educates.\u000a\u000aMadrigal is mostly happy with the partnership, but adds there are downsides. \u201cI lost some quality pre-K teachers to Pre-K 4 SA, because they can afford to pay a lot more than we can,\u201d he says. \u201cThat\u2019s kind of unfair, because if I could, I would, too.\u201d He\u2019s not eager to hand over data about how kids do at Harlandale after pre-K. \u201cI don\u2019t want the media to start comparing Pre-K 4 SA scores versus public schools\u2019,\u201d he says, \u201cbecause we\u2019re not all on the same equal playing table.\u201d\u000a\u000aEight of the 16 districts in San Antonio have opted to partner with Pre-K 4 SA, including the three largest ones in the city: Northside, North East and San Antonio, the central-city district. Sculley, the city manager, says the partner districts cover 85 percent to 90 percent of San Antonio\u2019s population of kids. Families from the districts that opted out can still attend Pre-K 4 SA, but families from partner districts have enrollment priority.\u000a\u000aMadrigal says his fellow superintendents who\u2019ve opted out of the Pre-K 4 SA alliance feel their pre-school programs are just as good, or that the city should just give them the extra pre-K funding directly. The wealthy and partially suburban Alamo Heights school district, for instance, was happy with its full-day pre-K program, says Sculley. So was the South San Antonio school district, which dropped out of Pre-K 4 SA in 2014. (Pre-K 4 SA supporters blame political turmoil in the district, which has fallen under state oversight and closed schools.) One district, East Central, joined the partnership last year, after Pre-K 4 SA agreed to expand to some unincorporated areas outside the city.\u000a\u000aAbove, Rey Madrigal, Superintendent of the Harlandale Independent School District, stands inside Harlandale High School. Below, Mayor Ron Nirenberg in a Pre-K classroom. They're both working to improve San Antonio's education systems. | Mark Peterson/Redux Pictures for Politico Magazine\u000a\u000aKevin Wolff, a Bexar County commissioner who represents northern San Antonio, campaigned against Pre-K 4 SA in 2012 and debated Julián Castro over it four times. Wolff argues the program duplicates the pre-K programs the local schools offer.\u000a\u000a\u201cIt\u2019s robbing Peter to pay Paul,\u201d Wolff says. \u201cThat has hurt our public school systems here. The city created a top-tier, first-class pre-K program, along with the salary and benefits that go with that. So it took the best resources, especially the best teachers.\u201d\u000a\u000aWolff believes preschool isn\u2019t the role of city government. \u201cIt\u2019s not whether pre-K is a good thing or a bad thing. It\u2019s should [this] level of government be participating?\u201d Instead of the city taking on early-childhood education, he argued in 2012, supporters should have pushed school districts and Texas\u2019 state government to step up. \u201cI don\u2019t want to be an enabler for another governmental entity to not do its job,\u201d he says.\u000a\u000a\u201cPolitically, I get it,\u201d Wolff says. \u201cIf it\u2019s for the children, it\u2019s very hard to say no to. And it looks good, politically. You can look back and say, \u2018See what I did.\u2019\u201d But he thinks other cities should not look to San Antonio as a model for tackling early-childhood education. \u201cFix the education system,\u201d he advises. \u201cDon\u2019t go create a whole new one.\u201d\u000a\u000aGeorge Rodriguez, a Tea Party activist, made similar points more pointedly when he campaigned against the 2012 tax hike. \u201cThe reason behind it all, in my opinion,\u201d says Rodriguez now, \u201c[was] to help Julián Castro have a platform to move on.\u201d\u000a\u000aTaking on pre-K as a city, Wolff argues, means the city doesn\u2019t take on something else. San Antonio, he notes, dedicates only a half-cent of its sales tax to operating Via, the local bus system, while Dallas, Houston, and Austin all dedicate a full cent of sales tax to transit. (Perhaps not coincidentally, the other three cities have all built light rail systems; San Antonio hasn\u2019t.) \u201cIf I were the city, and I had an eighth of a cent left, I\u2019d be much more likely to put it toward something I\u2019m supposed to do, rather than something else.\u201d\u000a\u000aThat very point came up this year in San Antonio\u2019s mayor\u2019s race. The nonpartisan contest pitted incumbent Ivy Taylor, a moderate with some conservative support, against city councilman Ron Nirenberg, a progressive in Castro\u2019s activist mold.. Transportation, not education, became a top issue in the race, with Nirenberg pushing for mass transit and other alternatives to cars. Taylor, attempting to also position herself as a transit advocate, declared that she would consider shifting Pre-K 4 SA\u2019s sales-tax funding to transportation when the tax expires in 2020. Pre-K 4 SA wasn\u2019t a \u201csacred cow,\u201d she told the editorial board of the San Antonio Express-News. It\u2019s one factor that led Castro, who\u2019d just returned home from Washington, to endorse Nirenberg, who supports Pre-K 4 SA.\u000a\u000aIn June, Nirenberg beat Taylor with 55 percent of the vote. \u201cI\u2019m going to continue to support [Pre-K 4 SA] as long as it works,\u201d the new mayor says. He\u2019s impressed with the students\u2019 growth results so far.\u000a\u000aImage Samantha Martinez Young just graduated from Pre-K 4 SA into kindergarten, but she already misses her teachers. | Mark Peterson/Redux Pictures for Politico Magazine\u000a\u000a\u201cThe state\u2019s job is public education,\u201d he acknowledges. \u201cIt isn\u2019t doing a very good job of that right now, and the consequences of that fall to local communities.\u201d Texas Governor Greg Abbott, a Republican, proposed expanding pre-K funding this year, but the Legislature slashed the new funds out of its budget. Does Pre-K 4 SA duplicate existing school programs? Maybe, says Nirenberg, but there\u2019s a population the existing programs aren\u2019t serving, or aren\u2019t all serving well. Besides, he argues, Pre-K 4 SA expands its reach beyond its 2,000 students with job-search and parenting support for families, competitive grants and teacher training. \u201cIf we were accomplishing all those things and reaching every student [without it],\u201d he says, \u201cthen we can argue about duplication.\u201d\u000a\u000aThis school year, an important benchmark will arrive for Pre-K 4 SA. Its first class of kids is starting third grade and will take Texas\u2019 standardized reading and math tests in the spring. In 2012, the Brainpower Initiative Task Force report declared that a key measurement of Pre-K 4 SA\u2019s success would be whether its kids posted better scores on Texas\u2019 third-grade tests than nonparticipating children. In 2016, 60 percent of third-graders in Harlandale, Rey Madrigal\u2019s district, scored satisfactory or better on the state reading test, while 63 percent did the same in math. Can Pre-K 4 SA alums do better?\u000a\u000a\u201cI told folks when I was campaigning for it in 2012, the way they should judge this program is by the numbers, by the evidence,\u201d says Castro, who\u2019s now back in San Antonio and writing a memoir. \u201cIf it demonstrates great results for these kids, then my hope is folks will support it again in 2020. If it doesn\u2019t, they shouldn\u2019t support it, or it should never be on the ballot again. That\u2019s still the standard.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe critics are watching. Rodriguez, who says he\u2019ll oppose renewal in 2020, says Pre-K 4 SA still lacks comparative statistics to make a case for itself. \u201cI don\u2019t see that there\u2019s a measurable success, compared to other pre-K programs, or Head Start programs,\u201d he says. He says stats he\u2019s seen about preschool programs show that kids\u2019 gains don\u2019t last. (Heckman\u2019s research says cognitive gains from preschool, including test scores, do fade over time, but social and emotional gains last into adulthood.)\u000a\u000aWolff says he doubts Pre-K 4 SA will fail on the ballot, citing a common conservative maxim. \u201cOnce government turns on a service,\u201d he says, \u201cturning it off is next to impossible.\u201d But he says the program\u2019s results may determine whether he campaigns against it again. \u201cObviously, if it\u2019s doing horrible, that gives me more impetus to fight it,\u201d he says.\u000a\u000aNirenberg is trying to manage expectations about the coming test results. \u201cThis is a brand-new program, and it\u2019s not going to be all aces right out of the gate,\u201d he says. \u201cIf it is, fantastic, but I\u2019m ready to see where the challenges are and get to work.\u201d\u000a\u000aIf he\u2019s reelected to another two-year term in 2019, Nirenberg will be in a position to lead a renewal campaign for the pre-K sales tax when it expires in 2020. \u201cIf this program continues to work as it is,\u201d says Nirenberg, \u201cand it\u2019s impacting the students as positively as we think it will, then yes, of course, why wouldn\u2019t I champion it?\u201d\u000a\u000aErick Trickey is a writer in Boston.\u000a\u000aThis story tagged under: Education
