aVBoris Johnson at an event in Sydney, Australia on July 27, 2017 | Brook Mitchell/Getty Images Boris Johnson: We will pay Brexit bill as we see it \u2018We are law-abiding, bill-paying people,\u2019 UK foreign secretary says.\u000a\u000aBritish Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson on Friday dismissed European estimates of what the U.K. owes the European Union as part of its departure from the bloc, saying \u201cwe should pay not a penny more, not a penny less, of what we think our legal obligations amount to.\u201d\u000a\u000aSpeaking to BBC Radio\u2019s Today program, Johnson explained why he said the EU could \u201cgo whistle\u201d for the U.K.\u2019s financial obligations, also known as the Brexit bill, which some reports put at \u20ac100 billion.\u000a\u000a\u201cThat\u2019s not a figure I recognize,\u201d Johnson said.\u000a\u000aAsked whether the U.K. is ready to pay a lower amount, Johnson said: \u201cOf course we will meet our obligations. We are law-abiding, bill-paying people.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cWe certainly have to meet our obligations,\u201d Johnson said, but added: \u201cI\u2019m not saying I accept Mr. [Michel] Barnier\u2019s interpretations of what our obligations are \u2026 we have to meet our legal obligations as we understand them, and that\u2019s what you would expect the British government to do.\u201d\u000a\u000aSpeaking about U.S. President Donald Trump\u2019s state visit, which has been criticized by many opposition figures, Johnson said the visit is \u201cmore likely [in] 2018 than this year.\u201d Johnson also said Trump \u201cgot it totally wrong\u201d in refusing to condemn white nationalist protesters in Charlottesville two weeks ago.
