aVTurkish President Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan addresses the media after the G20 summit in Hamburg, Germany | Sean Gallup/Getty Images Erdo\u011fan tightens grip on intelligence agency New powers allow president to veto appearance of MIT chief in court.\u000a\u000aISTANBUL \u2014 Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan gained control over his country\u2019s intelligence agency with a presidential decree on Friday in a further step toward consolidating his hold over the state.\u000a\u000aThe National Intelligence Organisation, known by its Turkish acronym MIT, will now report to the president. Previously, it was overseen by the prime minister.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe changes give President Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan control over domestic and overseas intelligence gathering,\u201d reported Turkey\u2019s state news agency Anadolu.\u000a\u000aShortly after last year\u2019s failed coup attempt, in which more than 240 people were killed, Erdo\u011fan announced he would attempt to rein in the country\u2019s military and intelligence services by bringing them under his own control.\u000a\u000aBut rather than bringing such a proposal before parliament, as he suggested last year, the change was made by presidential decree.\u000a\u000aSuch decrees, permitted under Turkey\u2019s ongoing state of emergency, allow Erdo\u011fan and his council of ministers to largely bypass parliament when issuing new rules and regulations.\u000a\u000aThe government has made liberal use of them for the past year, firing some tens of thousands of civil servants as Turkey sought to purge its state institutions of suspected coup sympathizers.\u000a\u000aAs part of the new rules, Erdo\u011fan will be able to veto prosecutors\u2019 requests to investigate the head of MIT or for him to testify as a witness in court.\u000a\u000aOpposition leader Kemal Kilicdaroglu has accused the government of attempting to cover up how much it knew of the coup attempt in advance by preventing the current MIT chief from testifying before a commission set up to investigate the failed putsch.\u000a\u000aThe MIT announcement was one of several changes decreed Friday. The government also ordered the suspension of 928 people, among them ministerial staff and military personnel, and the closure of three Kurdish media outlets.\u000a\u000aFollowing the government\u2019s narrow referendum victory in April, Turkey will gradually transition from a parliamentary system to a presidential republic until 2019, considerably expanding Erdo\u011fan\u2019s power.
