aVTrump coverage dwarfs Hurricane Harvey on cable news -- WSJ\u2019s Baker doubles down -- Gen Z tired of presidential politics?\u000a\u000aHURRICANE HARVEY WOULD BE THE TOP STORY ON CABLE NEWS UNDER MOST OTHER PRESIDENTS: But not in 2017. And not with President Donald Trump. Harvey, projected to make landfall in Texas potentially as a Category 3, could be the first major hurricane to strike in that part of the U.S. in 12 years. The last storms of that size to hit the U.S. from the Gulf of Mexico were Hurricanes Wilma and Katrina in 2005, the latter of which dominated news coverage in the U.S. for months and engulfed George W. Bush\u2019s presidency in controversy over relief efforts. And, of course, who could forget Superstorm Sandy, which owned the news cycle five years ago as it barreled up the East Coast. And yet Harvey, expected to make landfall in Texas this Saturday, was buried under a mound of Trump coverage on the cable news channels last night.\u000a\u000a\u2014Here were the lead stories last night on cable news:\u000a\u000aStory Continued Below\u000a\u000a\u2014MSNBC: \u201cAll In With Chris Hayes\u201d (8 to 9 p.m.) led with \u201cTrump & The Russians,\u201d discussing ongoing congressional probes into election tampering. Harvey was not covered. \u201cThe Rachel Maddow Show\u201d led with a story on Russia and Vladimir Putin. \u201cThe Last Word with Lawrence O\u2019Donnell\u201d led with \u201cTrump vs. Ryan,\u201d a segment on GOP infighting.\u000a\u000a\u2014CNN: \u201cAnderson Cooper 360\u201d (8 to 10 p.m.) led with \u201cIs Mexico Paying For The Wall?,\u201d discussing Tuesday\u2019s briefing exchange on the matter. Harvey was covered 49 minutes in. CNN aired a documentary about Elian Gonzalez from 10 to 11 p.m.\u000a\u000a\u2014Fox News: \u201cTucker\u201d led with \u201cErasing History,\u201d discussing the \u201cfate of U.S. monuments.\u201d Harvey was not covered. \u201cThe Five\u201d began with a segment on those questioning Trump\u2019s \u201cfitness\u201d and \u201cmental health.\u201d \u201cHannity\u201d led with a segment on the \u201cdestroy Trump media.\u201d\u000a\u000aTO BE FAIR: Every TV news outlet is gearing up for Harvey, and they all have crews on the ground in Texas. If for some reason today CNN, MSNBC or Fox News turn their focus to Trump, you can always turn to The Weather Channel, which went live at 5 a.m. and won\u2019t stop \u201cuntil further notice.\u201d Assuming Harvey doesn\u2019t weaken significantly, it should take over the news cycle at some point today.\u000a\u000a\u2014Still, the relatively modest coverage of Harvey so far is all the more surprising when you look back at coverage of Hurricane Matthew last October. Despite coming a month before the presidential election, coverage of Matthew swallowed up significant airtime.\u000a\u000aGood morning and welcome to Morning Media. I want to make Morning Media better and more useful to you, so please send me tips, ideas and feedback! I\u2019m on Twitter @alexweprin and on email at alexweprin@gmail.com. Morning Media is produced with help from Cristiano Lima (clima@politico.com / @ludacristiano). Archives. Subscribe.\u000a\u000aPROGRAMMING NOTE: Morning Media will not publish from Aug. 28-Sept. 4. Our next Morning Media newsletter will publish on Sept. 5. Enjoy the Labor Day weekend, and keep those tips coming!\u000a\u000aSARAH HUCKABEE SANDERS RETURNED TO THE PRESS PODIUM at the White House on Thursday for the first on-camera briefing since Aug. 2, which was before President Donald Trump went on an extended vacation. You may remember the last one for featuring senior aide Stephen Miller\u2019s contentious spat with CNN correspondent Jim Acosta -- whom he accused of having a \u201ccosmopolitan bias\u201d -- over the meaning of Emma Lazarus\u2019 poem on the Statue of Liberty. Feels like an eternity ago, no?\u000a\u000a\u2014The briefing featured Sanders downplaying discord between the president and congressional Republicans, hours after Trump lashed out at Republican leaders Mitch McConnell and Paul Ryan over their handling of the ongoing debt ceiling talks. Read POLITICO\u2019s take on the highlights here .\u000a\u000a\u2014It also featured reporters grilling Sanders on who exactly would be paying for Trump\u2019s proposed border wall with Mexico, which you can watch here .\u000a\u000a\u2014Trump\u2019s morning tweetstorm \u2014 which was, in fact, a tweetstorm \u2014 featured more critiques of media coverage of this week\u2019s speeches: \u201cThe Fake News is now complaining about my different types of back to back speeches. Well, there was Afghanistan (somber), the big Rally.....\u201d \u201c..(enthusiastic, dynamic and fun) and the American Legion - V.A. (respectful and strong). Too bad the Dems have no one who can change tones!\u201d\u000a\u000a\u2014The president also traded barbs with James Clapper, the former Director of National Intelligence turned-CNN analyst, who questioned Trump\u2019s \u201cfitness to be in this office\u201d Tuesday. \u201cWill he show you his beautiful letter to me?\u201d Trump tweeted. Clapper explained what Trump was talking about on CNN.\u000a\u000aFIRST IN MORNING MEDIA: Is \u201cGeneration Z\u201d shying away from presidential political coverage? They are, according to an exclusive breakdown from Oath -- the Verizon business unit that includes Yahoo, AOL and HuffPost -- of its aggregate news traffic over the past year. The new data shared with POLITICO's Cristiano Lima highlights a growing aversion to White House coverage among those born after 2001, and an increased interest in a more eclectic media diet. While an overwhelming majority of story visits across Oath sites by millennials, designated in this case as those born between 1981 and 2000, went toward coverage of presidential politics, at 87 percent, there was a marked drop off for those born later, with only 56 percent of their aggregate visits focused on West Wing politics. The youngest generation did, however, show a higher proportionate interest in other political stories, with 32 percent of their story hits falling along other political realms, the highest of any age group.\u000a\u000aTHE WALL STREET JOURNAL\u2019S GERARD BAKER IS NOT BACKING DOWN from his reported criticisms of his newsroom\u2019s coverage of President Trump\u2019s Tuesday rally in Phoenix. Baker panned a critical report of the event as \u201ccommentary dressed up as news reporting.\u201d According to The New York Times , which broke the news of Baker\u2019s post-rally admonishments, Baker doubled-down on the defense during a call with editors on Thursday, saying that that an \u201cassertion of challengeable contentions\u201d is not analysis.\u000a\u000a\u2014POLITICO\u2019s Jack Shafer on why he\u2019s \u201cnot mad\u201d at the Journal\u2019s top editor: \u201cComplicating any assessment of Baker\u2019s editorial philosophy is, of course, the fact that Rupert Murdoch owns the Journal, supports Trump and, as Times reporter Maggie Haberman tells us, he talks to the president nearly every day. Given Murdoch\u2019s history with phoning his editors almost daily, he must ring Baker daily, too. You don\u2019t have to connect the dots, Baker critics say, the dots connect themselves, and they glow.\u000a\u000a\u201cBut to fully convince me, you'll have to show me what is there, as opposed to what is not there in the paper that ends up plumping for Trump. Not calling Trump a liar and snipping news analysis from pieces does not automatically equal shilling. You can call it conservative coverage. You can call it soft. But you can\u2019t call it shilling.\u201d Read on here .\u000a\u000aARE JOURNALISTS THE OPPOSITION?: Point: This Nicholas Kristof column in The New York Times. He starts by noting that \u201cwe in journalism deserve to have our feet held to the fire. We make mistakes all the time, and too often we are superficial, sensationalist, unfair, defensive or diverted by shiny objects. Critics are right that we in the national media are often out of touch with working-class America, and distressingly often, we are lap dogs instead of watchdogs. Yet for all our failings, journalism remains an indispensable constraint on power. Trump has systematically tried to delegitimize the institutions that hold him accountable \u2014 courts, prosecutors, investigators, the media \u2014 and that\u2019s the context for his vilification of all them, for we collectively provide monitoring that outrages him.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u2014Counterpoint: Rich Lowry in this POLITICO Magazine piece. Republicans have always painted the media as an opposing force, but none with the aggressiveness of President Trump. Lowry\u2019s argument? \u201cHe\u2019s pushing against an open door with his audience because the media is, indeed, worse than ever before. As the media environment has fractured, organizations feel less obligation to try to cultivate a broader audience. And as politics becomes more culturally charged, the divide between the heartland and the coasts where the media lives and works becomes even more stark and important.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u2014In the midst of this debate, White House chief of staff John Kelly is taking matters in his own hands. According to POLITICO\u2019s Eliana Johnson and Nancy Cook, he is instituting a new system to monitor all information that gets to Trump\u2019s desk. The system is \u201cdesigned to ensure that the president won\u2019t see any external policy documents, internal policy memos, agency reports and even news articles that haven\u2019t been vetted.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u2014Recode\u2019s latest Recode Media podcast features a \u201cguided tour of pro-Trump media, from Drudge to Breitbart to Twitter trolls.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u2014Speaking of the pro-Trump media, Laura Ingraham\u2019s Lifezette described a photo of last year\u2019s Cleveland Cavaliers NBA championship parade as being \u201c5 miles of Trump supporters\u201d in Phoenix. Here\u2019s why that keeps happening.\u000a\u000aNEW YORK TIMES, BREITBART DOMINATE CHARLOTTESVILLE COVERAGE: That\u2019s one of the takeaways from a POLITICO analysis of how Twitter users were exposed to the events unfolding in Virginia. But there\u2019s a catch: liberals and conservatives were treated to widely-divergent views of the violent clashes, with left-leaning users reading reports of Trump\u2019s \u201cunequivocal boost\u201d of white supremacists and right-leaning users reading about Trump blasting the \u201calt-left\u201d media\u2019s \u201cone-sided Charlottesville reporting.\u201d The findings, courtesy of data from Cortico and the Laboratory for Social Machines at the MIT Media Lab Experience, underscore how deeply partisanship impacts news consumption, particularly on social media channels. Experience coverage of the events from across the political spectrum here .\u000a\u000aWHILE WE\u2019RE ON THE SUBJECT OF SOCIAL MEDIA, President Trump\u2019s latest verbal attacks on news outlets and their ensuring coverage of the rally as well as his selective blocking of Twitter followers and the crackdown of white supremacist sites in the wake of Charlottesville have all raised questions about who exactly should be allowed to determine what content ought to be blocked or limited online. So are these latest attempts to mediate what gets disseminated online a positive or negative step for freedom of speech?\u000a\u000a\u2014The short answer: it\u2019s complicated. Jason Kint, CEO of Digital Content Next, gives his take on the messy business of regulating controversial content on the web: \u201c[I]n part because of moral outrage, and pressure from media watchdogs and international governments\u2014tech platforms do step up willy-nilly to exert their control over content. Well-intentioned or not, the loose rules and vague promises of technology companies threaten to block the important role of the free media and the ability of the public to stay informed.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u2014Remember Valerie Plame? Well, she wants to buy Twitter. Why? So she can ban President Trump. \u201cWell, John Oliver joked last week about how we never imagined that the invention of Twitter would lead us to the brink of nuclear Armageddon,\u201d she told Vanity Fair . \u201cA good chuckle, but the people who understand how crises escalate\u2014I worked on counter-proliferation at the C.I.A.\u2014we\u2019re not laughing very hard. It is deadly serious.\u201d\u000a\u000aMUST READ: A centuries old letter written by Christopher Columbus, stolen from the Vatican, has turned up in\u2026 Atlanta. The Wall Street Journal\u2019s story . And: Did this book buy its way onto The New York Times bestseller list? According to this story , it sure appears so!\u000a\u000aSOUNDBITE: \u201cThe quote is accurate, context is not misleading, and while we of course don't agree on some things, the clip seems to me fair, not calling for any response.\u201d That\u2019s how famed scholar Noam Chomsky, in an email to our own Cristiano Lima, described a recent Tucker Carlson segment about the push to remove Confederate statues from state capitols that cited his work on identity politics. Chomsky, Carlson argued, emphasized the importance of economics over identity politics, a point the Fox News host touted as he referenced the \u201cold leftist\u201d Chomsky.\u000a\u000aREVOLVING DOOR:\u000a\u000a\u2014Foreign Policy has named Jonathan Tepperman editor-in-chief. Tepperman, who was previously managing editor of Foreign Affairs, will join the Graham Holdings-owned magazine in late September.\u000a\u000a\u2014Former Washington Post deputy national political editor Rebecca Sinderbrand has joined Yale University as a Block Visiting Lecturer where she will teach courses on journalism and politics.\u000a\u000a\u2014James Asher is joining the Associated Press\u2019 D.C. bureau as a news editor where he will oversee the AP\u2019s coverage of the ongoing probes into 2016 election interference and the Trump team.\u000a\u000aEXTRAS:\u000a\u000a\u2014Hugh Hefner\u2019s 25-year-old son Cooper Hefner wants to remake Playboy Magazine with an eye toward the future \u2014 and a progressive tinge. [ The Hollywood Reporter ]\u000a\u000a\u2014Eva Moskowitz, once in contention to be Trump\u2019s education secretary, has released a new memoir on education reform not unlike the president\u2019s \u201cArt of the Deal.\u201d She takes aim the media throughout for \u201csandbagging\u201d her, and calls out reporters by name. [ POLITICO ]\u000a\u000a\u2014Time\u2019s eclipse coverage shattered its record for most unique visitors in one day \u2014 previously established after the 2016 election \u2014 by more than 20 percent. [ Adweek ]\u000a\u000a\u2014Speaking of the eclipse, National Geographic is in hot water for using a composite photo of the event on its social media accounts [ Poynter ]\u000a\u000a\u2014Rupert Murdoch\u2019s News Corp. was cleared by antitrust regulators to buy Australia\u2019s Ten Network, a free-to-air television broadcaster. The company moved to solidify its Australian sports media dominance earlier this year by merging News Corp.\u2019s Fox Sports Australia and Telstra\u2019s Foxtel. [ Reuters ]\u000a\u000a\u2014Finding hope on \u201cHannity\u201d? LA Times columnist David Horsey said he did just that after watching the Fox News host give a reasonably measured take this week on President Trump\u2019s response to the violence in Charlottesville. [ Los Angeles Times ]\u000a\u000a\u2014New York Times Magazine staff writer Jonathan Mahler has inked a book deal with Random House. The new book will be \u201ca nonfiction narrative on New York City in the 1980s,\u201d according to the publisher, and \u201cwill explore the intersecting trajectories of the iconic figures who rose to fame during the period, including Donald Trump, Rudy Giuliani and Al Sharpton.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u2014As Labor Day nears, The New York Post\u2019s Page Six is gearing up to promote its upcoming syndicated TV show and look back at the last few months with a week-long \u201cPage Six Best of Summer\u201d series. Starting Monday, the series will look at the most memorable stories from the Summer in categories like relationships, scandals and \u201cbeach bodies.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u2014The neo-Nazi \u201cDaily Stormer\u201d website, taken down by web registrars for its highly-charged coverage of the violence in Charlottesville, has returned under a new domain name. [ The Daily Dot ]\u000a\u000a\u2014Projectiles, tear gas and breakings news: On the ground with The Arizona Republic reporters assigned to cover Trump\u2019s combative Tuesday rally. [ The Arizona Republic ]\u000a\u000a-- A 12-episode docuseries on the popular \u201cHumans of New York\u201d photography page is coming to Facebook. [ The Hollywood Reporter ]\u000a\u000a\u2014With the storied Village Voice shuttering its print publication and the closure of numerous other alt-weeklies, what will fill their gap in the digital age? [ Nieman Lab ]\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAuthors:
