aVMADRID \u2014 The terrorist attack in Barcelona resulted in unusual scenes of unity between the Spanish government and the regional executive of Catalonia.\u000a\u000aLet\u2019s see how long it lasts.\u000a\u000aAfter jihadists caused carnage on Barcelona\u2019s famous Las Ramblas and in the coastal town of Cambrils \u2014 the death toll now stands at 15 \u2014 Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy and Catalan President Carles Puigdemont appeared together three times to pay tribute to the victims and coordinate security operations.\u000a\u000aThe two leaders are normally at loggerheads over Catalan plans to hold an independence referendum on October 1 \u2014 a vote that Rajoy has vowed to prevent by all legal means necessary. But they have been at pains to stress unity and cooperation when it comes to fighting terror. No top official on either side has explicitly used the attacks to make political gains, be they pro-independence or pro-unity.\u000a\u000aYet there are subtle differences between Rajoy and Puigdemont\u2019s public pronouncements, reflecting underlying tensions. In his first appearance after the attacks, the Spanish PM spoke of the \u201cpain of the Spanish nation\u201d and didn\u2019t mention Catalonia once. Puigdemont didn\u2019t mention Spain once in his public remarks and repeatedly referred to Catalonia as a country.\u000a\u000aThe Spanish government has emphasized the importance of national security and intelligence services in managing the crisis \u2014 and played up the role of the national court judge leading the investigation. The Catalan cabinet, on the other hand, has singled out the work of the regional police \u2014 the Mossos d\u2019Esquadra \u2014 who dealt with the attacks on the ground and partly frustrated the strike in Cambrils.\u000a\u000aFrictions have also surfaced in the public communications of both governments, the most obvious being on Saturday when Spanish Interior Minister Juan Ignacio Zoido said the terrorist cell was \u201cpractically \u2026 totally dismantled,\u201d only to be contradicted just minutes later by a spokesman for the Catalan regional police, Albert Oliva. \u201cIt will be us who conclude the final result of the investigation when we consider that the cell is totally dismantled,\u201d Oliva said.\u000a\u000aA member of Rajoy\u2019s cabinet said cooperation between both sides had been \u201cgood.\u201d Yet an adviser to Catalan Vice President Oriol Junqueras described it as \u201ccold\u201d and \u201cbasic,\u201d pointing out that Rajoy didn\u2019t show up in Barcelona until very late on the day of the attack.\u000a\u000aOpposing views\u000a\u000aOfficials from both sides appear to have drawn different, and opposite, lessons from the attacks.\u000a\u000aWhereas Rajoy\u2019s cabinet member said a terror strike such as this should change political \u201cpriorities,\u201d referring to the Catalan government\u2019s push for secession, the Catalan official said local authorities have proven they can stand up to such a challenge on their own.\u000a\u000aFerran Casas, of digital newspaper Nació Digital, said politicians are holding back from criticizing each other because they\u2019re afraid doing so \u201cmay take its toll\u201d politically after such a tragedy.\u000a\u000aPau Marí-Klose, a sociology professor at Zaragoza University, added that \u201cfrontline politicians\u201d in Spain have learnt the lesson of the 2004 Madrid train bombings, which left 192 dead. The conservative government of the time, led by José María Aznar, attempted to link the carnage to domestic Basque terrorism. The strategy backfired and his successor, Rajoy, was beaten by José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero of the Socialists in an election three days after the attack.\u000a\u000aYet Mari-Klose is skeptical the apparent truce between unionist and independence supporters, and the governments of Madrid and Barcelona, can last much longer. He said the attitude of lower-ranked politicians and media commentators over the past few days has convinced him the tragedy will \u201cbe used brutally in the coming weeks.\u201d\u000a\u000aOn Friday, the day after the attacks, op-eds in Spain\u2019s biggest newspapers, El País and El Mundo, called for the Catalan government to abandon its push for secession and focus instead on the security of its citizens.\u000a\u000aPuigdemont responded in a radio interview, saying it was \u201cmiserable\u201d to link terror and the independence process, adding that his government\u2019s priority was to attend to the victims and catch the perpetrators.\u000a\u000aSome unionist commentators and politicians have chastised Catalan officials for giving their press conferences in Catalan instead of Spanish, and many more denounced Catalan Interior Minister Joaquim Forn for differentiating between Catalan and Spanish citizens when adding up the victims of the attack in a TV interview.\u000a\u000aPR victories\u000a\u000aOn the independence side, Puigdemont\u2019s chief press officer, Pere Martí, portrayed the meeting between the German and French foreign ministers \u2014 who flew in after the attack \u2014 with their Catalan counterpart Raül Romeva as a public relations victory. \u201cThey said that we wouldn\u2019t have international relations. That no one would receive us,\u201d Martí tweeted. He later deleted the message.\u000a\u000aInternational media have also come under fire. The international communications director of the Catalan government, Joan Maria Piqué, rebuked British newspaper the Telegraph for running a cartoon depicting a bull stopping a van, in reference to the attack in Barcelona. \u201cThis is Catalonia and bullfighting is forbidden in this country. Wrongest (and stereotyped) cartoon in ages,\u201d he tweeted.\u000a\u000aThis is Catalonia and bullfighting is forbidden in this country. Wrongest (and stereotyped) cartoon in ages cc @MStothard https://t.co/FMc9GsaIBC \u2014 Joan Maria Piqué \u200f\u0646 (@joanmariapique) August 18, 2017\u000a\u000aIf the rifts between Madrid and Barcelona were to increase, there\u2019s plenty of ammunition for both sides to engage in a dangerous blame game.\u000a\u000aThe Catalan government repeatedly asked Madrid to include Catalan regional police in international intelligence exchange mechanisms such as Europol, a request Madrid only recently agreed to and hadn\u2019t fully implemented at the time of last week\u2019s attacks.\u000a\u000aAlso, the national interior ministry had recommended city halls install obstacles or bollards in sensitive and busy parts of cities to make it more difficult for terrorists to strike. Barcelona didn\u2019t have such protections in place in Las Ramblas.\u000a\u000aFinally, the investigation has shown weaknesses in the security apparatus that may be exploited by both sides, such as the criminal record of the imam who alleged masterminded the plot \u2014 which Catalan authorities said they weren\u2019t aware of \u2014 and the time it took to link an explosion at a house in the village of Alcanar \u2014 where more than 100 gas tanks were found \u2014 and a terror cell.\u000a\u000a\u201cLet\u2019s see what happens in the coming hours,\u201d said Mari-Klose. \u201cThere\u2019s an attempt [by politicians] to avoid losing control of the whole thing, but I doubt that this can be done in a moment of such tension between both governments.\u201d
