aVNearly a year on from the referendum that began the U.K. on its journey to the EU exit door, the formal negotiations on the terms of Britain\u2019s departure are due to start Monday morning.\u000a\u000aThe talks will begin \u2014 as the EU27 have demanded \u2014 with discussions about citizens\u2019 rights, the Irish border and the U.K.\u2019s financial obligations (the so-called Brexit bill). But once sufficient progress has been made on those issues they will move into complex territory covering everything from trade and security to planes and fishing.\u000a\u000aHere\u2019s POLITICO\u2019s guide to the negotiators who will be on either side of the table.\u000a\u000aThe U.K.\u2019s Brexit negotiating team\u000a\u000aDavid Davis\u000a\u000aPosition: Secretary of state for exiting the European Union\u000a\u000aReal position: A true Brexit believer\u000a\u000aCareer highlight/lowlight: Standing down and flighting his own by-election in 2008 in protest at erosion of civil liberties\u000a\u000aU.K. Influence rating: 9/10\u000a\u000aThe odds-on favorite to become Conservative leader in 2005, Davis was pipped to the post by a young upstart named David Cameron. By 2016, he had gotten used to his place on the backbenches \u2014 a Tory freethinker and Brexiteer, though not of the head-banging variety. But in a textbook example of how that old wheel can turn, Cameron\u2019s post-referendum demise paved the way for Davis to return to government in the pivotal Brexit secretary role. Underestimated in Brussels but highly-rated by Theresa May, Davis, at 68-years-old, may view Brexit as his last great task in government (though he\u2019s now rumored to fancy a tilt at the top job again). Having argued for it for so long, he has a burning desire to get it right.\u000a\u000aOliver Robbins\u000a\u000aPosition: Prime Minister\u2019s EU adviser, Permanent secretary at the Department for Exiting the European Union\u000a\u000aReal position: Whitehall wunderkind turned Brexit supremo\u000a\u000aCareer highlight/lowlight: Kicked out of a parliamentary committee hearing for presenting \u201cunsatisfactory\u201d evidence\u000a\u000aU.K. Influence rating: 8/10\u000a\u000aTheresa May\u2019s Brexit sherpa, Robbins has been the U.K.\u2019s central figure behind closed doors ever since he was appointed by David Cameron as personal adviser on the EU in the days immediately after the June 2016 referendum. Robbins kept the role under May, and was also made permanent secretary \u2014 the top official \u2014 in David Davis\u2019s Department for Exiting the European Union. Despite his tall and imposing frame, colleagues describe him as a likeable chap, and he has been well-received by his counterparts in Brussels, with whom he has had regular contact in the run-up to negotiations. Having held senior office in the governments of Blair, Brown, Cameron and May, he is the ultimate Brexit \u201cgrown-up.\u201d\u000a\u000aPhilip Rycroft\u000a\u000aPosition: Second permanent secretary, Department for Exiting the European Union (DexEU)\u000a\u000aReal position: Keeping the United Kingdom together through Brexit\u000a\u000aCareer highlight/lowlight: Making transition from working with Europhile Nick Clegg, to delivering Brexit\u000a\u000aU.K. Influence rating: 6/10\u000a\u000aOlly Robbins\u2019 right-hand man, responsible for managing the department\u2019s overall policy and legislative program with Robbins expected to spend much of his time in detailed negotiations. He also has a role in the Cabinet Office heading up work on the constitution and devolution, so will be tasked with keeping an eagle eye on how Brexit affects Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland. A Europe expert who served in the cabinet of Leon Brittan in the European Commission. During the Tory-Lib Dem coalition government he was then Deputy Prime Minister Nick Clegg\u2019s right hand man in the civil service as director general in the DPM\u2019s office. Rycroft also has experience in the private sector as corporate affairs director at Hutchison Whampoa (Europe) Ltd, a multinational company with interests in a range of sectors including ports, energy, hotels and retail.\u000a\u000aTim Barrow\u000a\u000aPosition: U.K. permanent representative to the EU\u000a\u000aReal position: Diplomatic nous\u000a\u000aCareer highlight/lowlight: Making headlines with his dog-eared leather briefcase on Article 50 day\u000a\u000aU.K. Influence rating: 4/10\u000a\u000aWhat better man to usher in a new age of swashbuckling global Britain than one who looks like he just stepped out of a smoking room in the Colonial Office circa 1875? Barrow took over as the U.K.\u2019s ambassador to the EU after the dramatic resignation of the much liked and respected Ivan Rogers in January. The heavily-whiskered Barrow proved a much more manageable lead at the U.K.\u2019s permanent representation, keeping a low profile that will have suited Downing Street just fine, after Rogers\u2019 valedictory diatribe about \u201cmuddled thinking\u201d caused red faces in London. Previously the U.K\u2019.s man in Moscow, where he was a similarly low-key figure, Barrow is a Foreign Office man through and through. Having ably dispatched Theresa May\u2019s Article 50 letter on March 29, he is now expected to play the facilitator in the Brexit talks. However, he is not rated in Brussels, drawing unfavorable comparisons to his predecessor, and is not seen as having much influence in No. 10.\u000a\u000aAlex Ellis\u000a\u000aPosition: Director general at DExEU\u000a\u000aReal position: International man of mystery\u000a\u000aCareer highlight/lowlight: Debuting at the Foreign Office as part of the team that supported political transition in South Africa after the release of Nelson Mandela\u000a\u000aU.K. Influence rating: 7/10\u000a\u000aThe effervescent Ellis is a popular man at DExEU, where he is one of two director generals, said to take enjoyment in slipping Brexit soundbites into everyday conversation (\u201cAs a demonstration of our new deep and special partnership \u2026 would you like a cup of tea?\u201d). With top level Brussels experience \u2014 he worked in the office of former Commission President José Manuel Barroso from 2004 to 2007 \u2014 Ellis will bring vital insight into how the old place works. A former history teacher, his career spans South Africa, Portugal and most recently Brazil, where he was the U.K.\u2019s ambassador for three years before taking up the Brexit call.\u000a\u000aSarah Healey\u000a\u000aPosition: Director general at DExEU\u000a\u000aHealey is popular among staff in Davis\u2019 department and has a command of detail that would \u2014 and does \u2014 impress even Theresa May. She is a Brexit brainbox who is influential in Whitehall. A high-flyer like Robbins, Healey was brought into the Brexit department in July 2016 having risen through the ranks at the culture, work and pensions and education departments. She began her career in the prime minister\u2019s strategy unit, and has compared the cross-government work on Brexit to the task of putting on the 2012 London Olympics. She is also a quizzing maestro, who as a student won the BBC\u2019s cult quiz show University Challenge and twice competed in the Champions of Champions competition for Magdalen College, Oxford.\u000a\u000aSimon Case\u000a\u000aPostition: Director general for the U.K.-EU partnership, U.K. Representation to the EU (UKRep)\u000a\u000aHas led the U.K. government\u2019s work on exiting and seeking a new partnership with the European Union within the U.K. Representation to the EU. A high-flyer \u2013 former principal private secretary to David Cameron and Theresa May before being sent to Brussels. A key figure in UKRep.\u000a\u000aMark Bowman\u000a\u000aPosition: Director general, international finance at HM Treasury\u000a\u000aAt the Treasury, Bowman is responsible for advancing the U.K.\u2019s economic and financial interests internationally and in the EU \u2014 so he will be closely involved in talks on the \u201cBrexit bill.\u201d He leads the Treasury\u2019s work with foreign finance ministries, central banks and international institutions, including representing the U.K. in the Council of the EU\u2019s Economic and Financial Committee. He has been at the Treasury since 1995.\u000a\u000aGlyn Williams\u000a\u000aPosition: Director general at the Home Office\u000a\u000aA long-time civil servant (starting at the then Department of Trade and Industry in 1985) Williams is now responsible for policy in the U.K.\u2019s Border, Immigration and Citizenship System, including the development of a post-EU exit immigration regime. He also has experience of trade negotiations from his time in Geneva representing the U.K. at World Trade Organisation talks.\u000a\u000aCatherine Webb\u000a\u000aPosition: Director of market access and budget at DExEU\u000a\u000aBefore her current role at DExEU \u2014 responsible for policy on EU market access, goods and budgetary issues \u2014 Webb worked on an EU related portfolio in the Cabinet Office. She joined the civil service in 2000 and held various Treasury positions before taking up the role of economic and trade counselor at the British Embassy in Beijing.\u000a\u000aMark Philip Sedwill\u000a\u000aPosition: National security adviser to the prime minister\u000a\u000aWell known to Theresa May from his time as permanent secretary at the Home Office from February 2013 until April 2017 \u2014 when he was a late addition to the Brexit negotiating team. He joined the Foreign and Commonwealth Office in 1989 and since 2009 has served a series of high ranking positions in Afghanistan: including as the prime minister\u2019s special representative for Afghanistan and Pakistan.\u000a\u000aMatt Baugh\u000a\u000aPosition: Head of negotiation coordination unit, DExEu\u000a\u000aThe most influential figure in DExEU that no one has heard of. Heads up the department\u2019s A-team of officials tasked with coordinating all aspects of government policy on Brexit, reporting directly to Robbins. The team was set up by Robbins, raising eyebrows in DExEu. \u201cThis team are the super team. A circle within a circle,\u201d said a government official. Names of those serving in the team are not public. They draw out information from DExEU and other departments and coordinate it \u2014 that is their \u201cninja skill.\u201d \u201cA crack private office squad,\u201d the official said.\u000a\u000aKatrina Williams\u000a\u000aPosition: U.K. deputy permanent representative, UKrep\u000a\u000aA Brussels expert, having served in the Cabinet Office\u2019s European secretariat, coordinating Whitehall policy and advising the prime minister in the run-up to and during the U.K.\u2019s 2005 EU presidency.\u000a\u000aChris Jones\u000a\u000aPosition: Director general, DExEU\u000a\u000aResponsible for justice, security and migration.\u000a\u000aTom Shinner\u000a\u000aPosition: Director general, DExEU\u000a\u000aResponsible for cross-government policy coordination.\u000a\u000aJoanna Key\u000a\u000aPosition: Director general, DExEU\u000a\u000aResponsible for liaising with parliament, Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland, the crown dependencies and Gibraltar.\u000a\u000aSusannah Storey\u000a\u000aPosition: Director general, DExEU\u000a\u000aResponsible for strategic advice and economic analysis.\u000a\u000aAntony Phillipson\u000a\u000aPosition: Director general, DExEU\u000a\u000aResponsible for diplomatic engagement, issues relating to the Republic of Ireland and EU institutions.\u000a\u000aPeter Hill\u000a\u000aPosition: Prime minister\u2019s principal private secretary\u000a\u000aThe most senior civil servant inside No. 10 Downing Street, head of the prime minister\u2019s private office of officials. A former European Commission official and trade expert who worked under former Labour Minister and European Commissioner Peter Mandelson in Brussels.\u000a\u000aThe EU27 Brexit negotiating team\u000a\u000aMichel Barnier\u000a\u000aNationality: French\u000a\u000aFormal position: European chief negotiator for the United Kingdom exiting the European Union\u000a\u000aReal position: Preserving EU27 unity\u000a\u000aCareer highlight/lowlight: Key to France staging the 1992 Winter Olympics Games in Albertville.\u000a\u000aBrussels Influence rating: 9/10\u000a\u000aBarnier is the face of the Brexit talks for the EU27. He is officially a top EU civil servant \u2014 a director general in the European Commission \u2014 but Barnier is at heart a politician, meaning it will be very hard for the British team to put one over on him. The center-right pro-Europe Gaullist was elected as a MP in the 1970s. He held several top ministerial positions in France and was twice France\u2019s European commissioner: for regional policy and a decade later for the internal market and financial services. He knows Brussels and the main capitals intimately and has a reputation as a tough negotiator with a clear vision of where his powers and limits are. Some argue that Barnier is more powerful than many commissioners, but he operates within tight guidelines set by the European Council and approved by member countries and so has little room to maneuver.\u000a\u000aSabine Weyand\u000a\u000aNationality: German\u000a\u000aFormal position: European deputy chief negotiator for the United Kingdom exiting the European Union\u000a\u000aReal position: Staying on top of the details\u000a\u000aCareer highlight\u005clowlight: Deputy director general in the Commission\u2019s directorate general for trade.\u000a\u000aBrussels Influence rating: 7/10\u000a\u000aWeyand\u2019s experience as deputy at the Commission\u2019s powerful trade policy department will be invaluable in the later stages of the negotiations \u2014 plus her skills nicely complement Barnier\u2019s. In her trade role, Weyand is used to long and complex negotiations so she won\u2019t be fazed by anything the U.K. throws at her. In the official organigram of Barnier\u2019s Brexit taskforce, Weyand has direct oversight of the top staffers in charge of detailed aspects of the talks, from aviation to the U.K.\u2019s Brexit bill, meaning she will have to be across vast swathes of the detail. The word in Brussels is that Weyand\u2019s real job is to act as an envoy to Martin Selmayr, the Commission president\u2019s chief of staff, so that he can keep an eye on proceedings. Plus her German nationality keeps Barnier\u2019s team from being too French-dominated at the top.\u000a\u000aMartin Selmayr\u000a\u000aNationality: German\u000a\u000aFormal position: Head of cabinet of Jean-Claude Juncker, the president of the European Commission\u000a\u000aReal position: Feared as the hugely powerful \u201cmonster in the Berlaymont\u201d\u000a\u000aCareer highlight/lowlight: One of the few top Commission officials who makes headlines with his tweets\u000a\u000aBrussels influence rating: 8/10\u000a\u000aThe German former lawyer has run the daily operation of the European Commission since October 2014. Selmayr is powerful and he knows it, although he professes not to be. \u201cMy power is nonexistent. It derives only from what the president instructs me,\u201d he said. In reality, in policy areas from migration to the Greek crisis and of course Brexit, Selmayr has been a key actor establishing the Commission\u2019s position. Selmayr will be at the Brexit table representing the Commission \u2014 but even when he\u2019s not he will be there in spirit through Barnier\u2019s deputy, Sabine Weyand.\u000a\u000aDidier Seeuws\u000a\u000aNationality: Belgian\u000a\u000aFormal position: Head of the European Council\u2019s Article 50 task force\u000a\u000aReal position: Coordinator in chief\u000a\u000aCareer highlight/lowlight: He was the spokesman of the former Belgian prime minister and now Brexit coordinator in the European Parliament Guy Verhofstadt\u000a\u000aBrussels influence rating: 5/10\u000a\u000aSeeuws, a Belgian diplomat, was appointed just days after the Brexit vote to head the Council\u2019s Article 50 task force in the Council \u2014 ahead of Barnier himself. The Council\u2019s swift move was seen by some Commission top officials as a power-grab. But politically savvy Seeuws was not appointed to compete with Barnier but to do his part in the Council, shuttling between national capitals in order to iron out differences in the talks. Seeuws is not seen as a controversial figure and the diplomat, who worked in the Belgian foreign ministry and the Belgian permanent representation to the EU, is credited with unlocking a deal on the European patent system, an issue that had resisted compromise for 30 years. He is a keen cyclist.\u000a\u000aStéphanie Riso\u000a\u000aNationality: French\u000a\u000aFormal position: Director for strategy, coordination and communication\u000a\u000aReal position: To prevent the U.K. dividing the EU27 side on the Brexit bill\u000a\u000aCareer highlight/lowlight: Former head of unit for the EU\u2019s multiannual financial framework\u000a\u000aBrussels influence rating: 5/10\u000a\u000aRiso was one of the first appointments Barnier made to his team, sending a clear message \u2014 there will be no free-riding and the U.K. must pay what it owes. She has in-depth expertise in EU budget talks and their endless financial and legal implications. The context for those talks is almost impossible because it requires unanimity among the EU countries. Brexit might be light relief by comparison.\u000a\u000aGeorg Riekeles\u000a\u000aPosition: Inter-institutional affairs team leader\u000a\u000aA long-time staffer of Michel Barnier in recent years. Norwegian.\u000a\u000aTristan Aureau\u000a\u000aPosition: Inter-institutional affairs team\u000a\u000aA young French diplomat.\u000a\u000aRandolph de Battista\u000a\u000aPosition: Inter-institutional affairs team (rotating presidency secondment)\u000a\u000aA staffer from the rotating presidency in charge of liaising with the Council. De Battista is from Malta. From July the position will belong to Uku Särekanno, the head of staff and the presidency preparation team in the Estonian permanent representation.\u000a\u000aEugenia Dumitriu-Segnana\u000a\u000aPosition: Legal affairs expert for strategy, coordination and communication\u000a\u000aFormer lawyer in the Council of the EU. Romanian.\u000a\u000aStefaan De Rynck\u000a\u000aPosition: Seconded head of unit \u2014 relations with think tanks and communication\u000a\u000aFormer Barnier spokesman when he was commissioner but also head of unit in the financial services department. Belgian.\u000a\u000aNicola Pesaresi\u000a\u000aPosition: Head of cluster \u2014 horizontal issues, cross-cutting policies and level playing field\u000a\u000aFormer competition official with expertise on state aid. Italian.\u000a\u000aWard Mohlmann\u000a\u000aPosition: Financial stability\u000a\u000aFormer policy officer in the Financial Services and Capital Markets Union department. Dutch.\u000a\u000aTadhg O\u2019Brian\u000a\u000aPosition: Energy and climate, environment\u000a\u000aStaffer at the Energy department. Early in his career he worked for the Northern Ireland devolved government. Irish.\u000a\u000aAurora Mordonu\u000a\u000aPosition: Economic analysis\u000a\u000aFormer economist in the Economic and Financial Affairs department. Romanian.\u000a\u000aThomas Liefländer\u000a\u000aPosition: Level playing field\u000a\u000aFrom the Competition department. German.\u000a\u000aFrançois Arbault\u000a\u000aPosition: Head of cluster \u2014 internal market and sectorial policies\u000a\u000aFormer staffer under Barnier when he was commissioner. His cluster will deal with issues relating to the internal market in goods and non-financial services (the team currently does not include anyone covering the financial services brief). French.\u000a\u000aMarie Simonsen\u000a\u000aPostition: Free movement of citizens, employment\u000a\u000aFormerly legal affairs coordinator at the Employment, Social Affairs and Inclusion department. Danish.\u000a\u000aPeter Sorensen\u000a\u000aPosition: Aviation\u000a\u000aFormer policy officer on aviation safety in the Mobility and Transport department. Danish.\u000a\u000aPhilippe Bertrand\u000a\u000aPosition: Head of cluster \u2014 budget, spending commitments and programs\u000a\u000aBertrand\u2019s job will be to help get the best deal for the EU27 on the U.K.\u2019s financial settlement. French.\u000a\u000aBence Toth\u000a\u000aPosition: Agriculture, fisheries and maritime policy\u000a\u000aFrom the Agriculture and Rural Affairs department. Hungarian.\u000a\u000aNorbert Gacki\u000a\u000aPosition: Budget\u000a\u000aFrom the Budget department. Polish\u000a\u000aAntonio Fernandez-Martos\u000a\u000aPosition: Head of cluster \u2014 international agreements and customs\u000a\u000aAn economist who is the head of unit for trade investments and joined Barnier\u2019s Brexit task force in October. His career has moved back and forth between the Spanish civil service and the European Commission. Spanish.\u000a\u000aNina Obermaier\u000a\u000aPosition: External relations and foreign and security policy\u000a\u000aWorked on the team for EU-Switzerland relations in the EU\u2019s diplomatic service. German.\u000a\u000aStefan Fuehring\u000a\u000aPosition: Justice and home affairs, health and food safety (external aspects)\u000a\u000aComes from the Commission\u2019s secretariat-general. German.
