aVJust one week ago, Steve Bannon left his post as President Donald Trump's chief strategist. He's been busy ever since. | Mark Wilson/Getty Images Media Bannon\u2019s back: A week in Breitbart headlines\u000a\u000aIt\u2019s been one week since Steve Bannon was ousted from his post as President Donald Trump\u2019s chief strategist and returned to his perch as executive chairman of Breitbart News, where he pledged to \u201ccrush the opposition.\u201d\u000a\u000aPOLITICO monitored the right-wing website\u2019s home page this week to see whether Bannon was making good on his promise. We found that the site heartily mocked West Wing aides that Bannon had clashed with \u2013 including Trump\u2019s son-in-law and top adviser Jared Kushner and national security adviser H.R. McMaster \u2013 as well as Republican congressional leaders who have long been a target of Breitbart\u2019s ire. The site also didn\u2019t spare the president on his plans for the war in Afghanistan and his administration\u2019s immigration policy.\u000a\u000aStory Continued Below\u000a\u000aHere\u2019s a look at some of Breitbart\u2019s top headlines from the week.\u000a\u000aHitting White House aides\u000a\u000aPablo Martinez Monsivais/AP\u000a\u000aBreitbart took aim at several of the president\u2019s top aides in the White House, particularly Kushner and economic adviser Gary Cohn. The site mocked Kushner\u2019s trip to the Middle East and took offense to an interview Cohn gave, criticizing Trump\u2019s response to the recent white supremacist rally in Charlottesville, Virginia. (Bannon reportedly does not get along with either of them.)\u000a\u000aTweaking Paul Ryan and Mitch McConnell\u000a\u000aPablo Martinez Monsivais/AP\u000a\u000aThe leaders of the Republican Party were roundly criticized by Breitbart, as they often are. The site highlighted Trump\u2019s comments blaming Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell and House Speaker Paul Ryan for the state of negotiations around raising the debt ceiling prominently on the home page, and hit McConnell for his poor approval rating in a recent poll.\u000a\u000aQuestioning Trump\u2019s Afghanistan strategy \u2014 and H.R. McMaster\u2019s influence\u000a\u000aEvan Vucci/AP\u000a\u000aBreitbart was uncharacteristically critical of Trump on Monday after he delivered a foreign policy address announcing a troop surge in Afghanistan, a move Bannon reportedly opposed. But the site made a point to spin the decision as the result of bad advice from McMaster, who tangled with Bannon during his time at the White House.\u000a\u000aCovering Confederate monuments\u000a\u000aSteve Helber/AP\u000a\u000aBreitbart was eager to cover the debate on what to do about the remaining Confederate monuments around the country and the growing movement to remove them in the wake of the violence in Charlottesville (the site dubbed it \u201cmadness\u201d).\u000a\u000aBannon recently told The New York Times that he wants Democrats to talk more about the issue because he thinks it\u2019s good politically for Trump: \u201cThe race-identity politics of the left wants to say it\u2019s all racist,\u201d he said. \u201cJust give me more. Tear down more statues. Say the revolution is coming. I can\u2019t get enough of it.\u201d\u000a\u000aCalling for the wall and immigration restriction\u000a\u000aGuillermo Arias/AFP/Getty Image\u000a\u000aThere\u2019s ongoing debate in the White House about what to do on immigration, and Trump continues to demand money for his proposed wall on the U.S.-Mexico border (at a rally on Tuesday, he threatened to shut down the government if he didn\u2019t get it). Breitbart was apoplectic about reports that some White House aides are \u201cchoking out\u201d at Trump\u2019s \u201cwinning populist agenda\u201d by opposing the border wall.\u000a\u000aCheering Trump\u2019s Phoenix rally\u000a\u000aRick Scuteri/AP\u000a\u000aBreitbart\u2019s home page drew plenty of attention to Trump\u2019s combative, freewheeling rally speech in Phoenix, Arizona, on Tuesday, cheering the president\u2019s attacks on the media for its \u201clies\u201d and complaining about protesters. It also gave Kelli Ward, a right-wing primary challenger to Sen. Jeff Flake, a shout-out.\u000a\u000aAuthors:\u000a\u000aThis story tagged under: Breitbart News\u000a\u000aStephen Bannon
