aVU.S. National Security Advisor H. R. McMaster | Brendan Smialowski/AFP via Getty Images McMaster: No military action against Venezuela anticipated in the \u2018near future\u2019 White House imposes new economic sanctions against crisis-hit South American country.\u000a\u000aNational security adviser H.R. McMaster said Friday that the White House does not anticipate taking any \u201cmilitary actions\u201d against Venezuela \u201cin the near future.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cObviously all our decisions would be made in conjunction with our partners in the region,\u201d McMaster told reporters at the afternoon press briefing. \u201cNo military actions are anticipated in the near future.\u201d\u000a\u000aMcMaster and Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin briefed reporters on new economic sanctions the administration is imposing against Venezuela after President Nicolás Maduro initiated an overhaul of the country\u2019s constitution. The White House has declared Maduro\u2019s regime a dictatorship.\u000a\u000aEarlier this month, President Donald Trump suggested that he might consider taking military action against the country, saying, \u201cWe have many options for Venezuela, including a possible military option, if necessary.\u201d\u000a\u000aMcMaster, taking questions from reporters on Friday, said Trump\u2019s advisers \u201calways look at a broad range of contingencies and how this might evolve in the future\u201d and present that information to the president.
