aVGerman Chancellor Angela Merkel | Christof Stache/AFP via Getty Images UK must pay Brexit bill, says Angela Merkel German chancellor said bill was not a fine but an \u2018obligation\u2019 that Britain had entered into.\u000a\u000aGerman Chancellor Angela Merkel warned the U.K. on Saturday that it would have to pay a settlement to leave the EU, denying that the obligation amounted to a \u201cfine.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cThis is about obligations that Great Britain has entered into and that naturally must remain on the books,\u201d Merkel said in her weekly podcast published Saturday ahead of the latest round of talks next week, Bloomberg reported. \u201cIt\u2019s not about the cost of divorce \u2014 that makes it sound like fines. We\u2019re still at the very start of these negotiations.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe divorce bill, or how much the U.K. should pay the EU upon leaving the bloc, is one of the most contentious issues in the Brexit talks. The EU has already outlined a full list of bodies and funds that it believes must be covered by the financial settlement. Estimates of the bill have ranged up to \u20ac100 billion.\u000a\u000aBrussels has told Britain to come forward with a proposal for how to calculate the bill or risk derailing next week\u2019s Brexit talks \u2014 something it has so far declined to do, preferring to critique the EU proposal.\u000a\u000aBoris Johnson, the British foreign secretary, said he did not \u201crecognize\u201d the \u20ac100 billion figure but added that \u201cwe should pay not a penny more, not a penny less, of what we think our legal obligations amount to.\u201d
p227
aVEU Competition Commissioner Margrethe Vestager | Aurore Belot/AFP via Getty Images EU launches in-depth probe into Bayer\u2019s purchase of Monsanto The deal has sparked intense opposition in Europe and further afield.\u000a\u000aMargrethe Vestager, European commissioner for competition, opened an in-depth probe into Bayer\u2019s controversial $66 billion acquisition of Monsanto on Tuesday, citing a list of competition concerns that will almost certainly drag the review into 2018.\u000a\u000aThe market for weedkillers is at the forefront of the probe, with investigators warning Germany\u2019s Bayer is one of only a few companies to produce a genuine alternative to Missouri-based Monsanto\u2019s market-leading pesticides based on the controversial herbicide glyphosate. They also said the merger risked reducing competition for developing and marketing new seeds and plant traits.\u000a\u000aThose preliminary conclusions will lift the hopes of an army of critics, who view Vestager as the last chance to kill a tie-up. The deal has sparked intense opposition in Europe and further afield, with environmentalists and hundreds of thousands of petitioners calling on the Danish commissioner to block it.\u000a\u000aMuch of the public furore about glyphosate, however, lies well beyond the scope of Vestager\u2019s investigation. The chemical is a subject of intense debate primarily because the EU must decide by the end of the year whether to renew its license for up to 15 years for use by farmers, who say it is critical to maintain yields, while scientists continue to debate whether it causes cancer.\u000a\u000a\u201cOne monster corporation controlling our food is a bad idea for farmers and citizens everywhere\u201d \u2014 Nick Flynn\u000a\u000a\u201cWe need to ensure effective competition so that farmers can have access to innovative products, better quality and also purchase products at competitive prices,\u201d Vestager said, announcing the so-called Phase II investigation.\u000a\u000aThe Commission noted the merged entity \u201cwould hold both the largest portfolio of pesticides products and the strongest global market positions in seeds and traits, making it the largest integrated company in the industry.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe Commission has the power to either block mergers or demand divestments by the companies.\u000a\u000aBayer said it would continue to \u201cwork constructively with the Commission with a view to obtaining the Commission\u2019s approval of the transaction by the end of this year.\u201d Monsanto had no immediate comment.\u000a\u000aAgri-chemical mega-mergers\u000a\u000aThe deal, announced in September 2016 amid a wave of consolidation between the giant agri-chemical companies, has made slow progress on the regulatory front. The U.S. Department of Justice continues to examine the deal, and regulators in Australia, Brazil and Canada have also been looking into it. South Africa has conditionally approved the merger.\u000a\u000aIn Europe, investigators have honed in on the companies\u2019 overlapping businesses in vegetable seeds and field crop seeds, in particular oilseed rape and cotton, plus Bayer\u2019s position as one of the main rivals to Monsanto on the market for developing and introducing traits to plants.\u000a\u000aThe companies\u2019 activities in developing and selling \u201cnon-selective herbicides\u201d also attracted attention. \u201cBayer produces glufosinate ammonium, also a non-selective herbicide and one of the very few alternatives to glyphosate,\u201d the Commission said.\u000a\u000aRegulators also said they would examine how the advent of digital agriculture and the use of Big Data analyses could reinforce strong market positions.\u000a\u000aMore than a million people globally have signed a variety of petitions against the deal, while thousands of campaigners have bombarded Vestager online asking her to block what they call Bayer and Monsanto\u2019s #mergerfromhell. In a letter to petitioners published Tuesday, Vestager said she had received more than 50,000 petition emails and more than 5,000 postcards and letters on the case but warned she could only examine the deal on competition grounds.\u000a\u000aBayer and Monsanto\u2019s merger is the last of the trio of mega-mergers that have dramatically consolidated the agri-chemical industry.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe other concerns you raise are handled by my colleagues and national authorities and are subject to European and national rules to protect food safety, consumers, the environment and the climate,\u201d she wrote.\u000a\u000aCampaigners nonetheless expect her to block the deal.\u000a\u000a\u201cOne monster corporation controlling our food is a bad idea for farmers and citizens everywhere,\u201d said Nick Flynn, legal director at Avaaz, a campaign group. \u201cThat\u2019s why over a million people are hoping Commissioner Vestager comes back with a long term rejection of Monsanto and Bayer\u2019s marriage from hell.\u201d\u000a\u000aBayer and Monsanto\u2019s merger is the last of the trio of mega-mergers that have dramatically consolidated the agri-chemical industry. Two of the deals \u2014 Dow\u2019s tie-up with DuPont and ChemChina\u2019s acquisition of Syngenta \u2014 obtained EU clearance at the end of long probes and on condition they sold off some businesses.
