aVLouise Linton, the wife of Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin, posted a cringe-worthy Instagram, followed by an oblivious public reply to a commenter yesterday, bragging about her designer clothes and the couple\u2019s vast wealth. In a now-deleted post, Linton, 36, a Scottish-born actress (her credits include exactly one episode each of Cold Case and CSI: NY ), stepped off a U.S. Air Force jet on the couple\u2019s federal government trip to Kentucky\u2019s Fort Knox and, like any dignified person might do in that situation, proceeded to Instagram the photo evidence along with her outfit credits, which were not tagged in the post, but hashtagged in succession: \u201c#roulandmouret pants, #tomford sunnies, #hermesscarf, #valentinorockstudheels #valentino.\u201d\u000a\u000aIt didn\u2019t end there for Linton, who married 54-year-old Mnuchin, a former Goldman Sachs executive and film producer who is now fifth in line to the presidency, in June. When Instagram user @jennimiller29 commented, \u201cGlad we could pay for your little getaway #deplorable,\u201d Linton snapped back in a lengthy, deeply privileged, and totally oblivious reply.\u000a\u000a\u201cHave you given more to the economy than me and my husband? Either as an individual earner in taxes OR in self-sacrifice to your country?\u201d Linton asked. \u201cI\u2019m pretty sure we paid more in taxes toward our day \u2018trip\u2019 than you did. Pretty sure the amount we sacrifice per year is a lot more than you\u2019d be willing to sacrifice if the choice was yours.\u201d After inserting strong-arm and kiss-face emojis, Linton quipped: \u201cYou\u2019re adorably out of touch.\u201d\u000a\u000aWhich was a pretty funny thing to say given that she is newly married to someone worth an estimated $300 million, is wearing $995 shoes, and, after deplaning a military jet, is framing their federally mandated tax bill and/or Mnuchin\u2019s White House role as a \u201csacrifice.\u201d Sadly, this \u201cpoor little rich people in government\u201d narrative has its roots with none other than the Trump family, who, during the presidential campaign, repeatedly characterized President Trump\u2019s candidacy as a \u201cgreat sacrifice.\u201d Linton may want to talk to some Gold Star families and revisit this argument.\u000a\u000aA Treasury Department official declined to comment to The New York Times regarding Linton\u2019s post, though they did clarify that the Mnuchins reimbursed the government for the trip, and that Linton was not compensated by any of the labels she promoted with hashtags. Still, this mini-scandal is ill-timed for Mnuchin, who is already under fire of late, after more than 300 graduates from his alma mater, Yale, wrote an open letter imploring him to resign in protest of Trump\u2019s comments equating Nazis and white supremacists in Charlottesville with their counter-protesters. Mnuchin replied by denying the president supports hate groups and, referring to the raging \u201cculture wars,\u201d saying that \u201csome of these issues are far more complicated than we are led to believe by the mass media.\u201d\u000a\u000aLinton has since deleted the post and made her Instagram account private. In the meantime, perhaps she puts on her #valentinorockstudheels, walks over to the East Wing, and offers her assistance with First Lady Melania Trump\u2019s long-in-the-works anti-cyberbullying initiative?
