aVBritish Prime Minister Theresa May as she tours the Alexander Dennis bus and coach manufacturers factory in Guildford, south of London, on August 23, 2017 | Pool photo by Matt Durham/Getty Images Theresa May says deportation letters sent in error Some 100 EU nationals received a UK government letter telling them to leave the country.\u000a\u000aBritish Prime Minister Theresa May on Wednesday said her government had mistakenly sent up to 100 letters to EU nationals living in the U.K. ordering them to leave the country or face deportation, the Guardian reported.\u000a\u000aMay said the Home Office made an \u201cunfortunate error\u201d after one of the letters was posted on social media by Eva Johanna Holmberg, a Finnish academic who has lived in Britain for years but was told she had a month to pack up and leave.\u000a\u000a\u201cI understand they [the government] moved quickly to contact the people who had received these letters and assure them they were not going to be deported and I want to assure EU nationals here in the U.K. that their rights and status in the U.K. have not changed,\u201d May said.\u000a\u000aThe letter to Holmberg said that if she did not leave the country of her own accord, the Home Office would give \u201cdirections for [her] removal.\u201d It added that she was \u201ca person liable to be detained under the Immigration Act.\u201d\u000a\u000aA government spokesperson said \u201cwe are absolutely clear that the rights of EU nationals living in the U.K. remain unchanged.\u201d
