aVNew York\u2019s brash new landlord can afford to sit pretty. He has powerful friends, a beautiful wife, a football team, and some of the choicest turf in Manhattan. It\u2019s wild, it\u2019s crazy. Isn\u2019t it?\u000a\u000aRoy Cohn has a problem. It is mid-November, a peak month for New York hotel bookings, and an out-of-town client of his law firm, Saxe, Bacon & Bolan, is stuck for a room for the night. Another lawyer might tell the fellow to hike his grip down to the "Y," but Cohn is known around town as a fixer of sorts, a reputation that must constantly be nurtured by small favors. He decides to call another client, who happens to own two hotels in the city, the Grand Hyatt and the Barbizon Plaza. In the powerful New York triangle of politics, law, and real estate, the two men have what passes for a friendship. It is 8:30 in the morning, but the voice on the other end of the phone is full of brio. "Roy M. Hi. What's up? Who? Sorry, Roy, I think the Grand Hyatt is full. But how about the Barbizon? Hold on. Let me find out." There follows a partially muffled shout to an assistant in the next office to line up the room, then he's back on the phone. "Okay, I think we can book him into the Barbizon. Only for you, Roy."\u000a\u000aOnly for you, Roy. Or you, Hugh. Or Abe or Ed or Mario. Meet Donald Trump. Age 38. Eyebrows by Henry Luce. The sandy hair\u2014longish on the sides in a Chamber of Commerce sort of way and brushed flat over the ears\u2014by George Steinbrenner. The six-foot-two-inch frame is trim but well-nourished. The hands small and neatly groomed. The suit is blue and stylish\u2014maybe a little too flared in the leg for someone who lives east of the Hudson. About the only thing that gives away this striver from an outer borough are his cuff links: huge mollusks of gold and stone the size of half-dollars.\u000a\u000aThis story was originally published in the May 1984 issue of GQ.\u000a\u000aOn this brisk, fall morning, a visitor making one of many journeys to Donald Trump's offices on the twenty-sixth floor of Trump Tower in midtown Manhattan gets out of his cab in front of the building. Double-parked outside is a half-block-long Cadillac stretch limo with "DJT" vanity plates.\u000a\u000aUpstairs, not surprisingly, Trump is on the horn. "Yeah, eleven-thirty would be much better, Ben. I'll cancel somebody else and move them around a little bit. Okay pal. See you then." He swivels around to greet his new arrival. "That man is the head of an insurance company, a major one. He's having some people from California come to New York tomorrow, and he wants to show them some real estate. They represent a $4 billion account, and the only real estate they want to see is Trump Tower. That's all they want to see. It's crazy."\u000a\u000aEDITOR\u2019S PICK\u000a\u000aSuch is the newfound fame of Donald Trump. Not too long ago he was dismissed by the real estate establishment as little more than a mauve-suited sharpie with a big mouth. He got rid of the suits. Then, with a style that was considered bold in some quarters and smarmy in others, he cut a broad swath through prime blocks of Manhattan real estate, plastering the family name on any blank surface that rose and shined and, not incidentally, building more in the city of New York than anyone else in the past five years. Trump refurbished the bankrupt Commodore Hotel adjacent to Grand Central Station and turned it into one of the city's more spectacular new luxury hotels, the 1407-room Grand Hyatt. To tidy up the view, he cleaned and caulked the Forty-second Street facade of Grand Central, then leased and renovated the old Vanderbilt Athletic Club and renamed it The Tennis Club. Trump optioned a twenty-five-acre site of decaying waterfront property from the defunct Penn Central Railroad and then talked the city into using the site for its $450 million Convention Center. In May 1983 he finished Trump Tower, and last March opened Trump Plaza, a new, forty-story cooperative development on New York's Upper East Side, a block away from Bloomingdale's. Another project, Harrah's at Trump Plaza, the largest casino in Atlantic City, opens this month.\u000a\u000aTo the gray world of New York real estate, ruled for so long by the Tishmans, the Fishers, the Rudins, the LeFraks, and now the Reichmanns, Trump has infused a brand of freewheeling self-aggrandizement not seen since the days of the late, great Bill Zeckendorf. "My projects now sort of self-promote," says Donald. "And if there's a reason I'm good promotionally, it's that I know what people want. I am good in challenging situations. What I like is for people to tell me something can't be done when I think it can. In real estate, you deal with some very smart, very devious people. They're the sharpest wolves in the world. I've competed against them and I've come out fine."\u000a\u000aNowhere is this mix of real-estate hard sell and showbiz brashness more apparent than in Trump Tower, the trim, bronze, sixty-eight-story office, retail, and condominium complex that opened last year on the site of the old Bonwit Teller building at Fifth Avenue and Fifty-sixth Street.\u000a\u000aThere are only two types of people who live on Fifth Avenue in midtown: homeless derelicts, who sleep over the hot-air grates in front of Saks, and well-groomed members of the cabaret set, who prefer to set down roots in a neighborhood where groceries or even a bar of soap are a taxi ride away. The latter have decided to call Trump Tower's 268 condominium apartments home. (Trump has sold the apartments in the building as condominiums rather than co-ops. It ensures that no one with the right amount of money, regardless of its origins, will be given the heave-ho by a snooty co-op board.) For most new tenants, like Johnny Carson, Paul Anka, Sophia Loren, and Steven Spielberg, Trump Tower will serve as a New York pied-à-terre. Across the hall from Johnny's new digs, the folks about to move in have been busy installing a swimming pool in their apartment. "It's actually three apartments\u2014one's a duplex," says Trump. "Two for living in and one just for the pool. Lots of saunas. It's strange. It's an unbelievable situation. There are some people that won't be here more than a week a year. It's crazy."\u000a\u000aThat may be an understatement. Try $600,000 for a cramped, L-shaped one-bedroom. The price is a million or more for the ninety-one larger apartments. When even the European cognoscenti balked at paying $12 million for the penthouse triplex, Trump took the place for himself.\u000a\u000aDown below on street level is where the rabble is supposed to ooh and aah. Entering the foyer, with its peach marble floor, ceiling and walls, produces a sort of vertigo. On rainy days, a spectator sport develops near the entrance where, unbeknownst to the first-time visitor, the floor cants somewhat to the six-story shopping atrium. There, with the marble greased by the water, tanned lady shoppers hit the incline, pick up speed and momentarily hydroplane before skittering to flat ground and safety.\u000a\u000aAh, but for the nimble of foot and the stout of pocketbook, Trump Tower's atrium is a veritable EPCOT for the advanced shopper. Retail tenants, says Trump, were chosen largely for their moneyed cachet. And indeed, shops such as Loewe, Asprey, Harry Winston, Cartier, and Buccellati can tame even the most hearty of spendthrifts. So intimidating are these outfits that at Christmastime last year, a number of tourists were seen tentatively peeking in through the window of the atrium's smoke shop, apparently afraid to enter this hallowed purveyor of magazines, cigarettes, and gum. "It's the greatest group of stores ever assembled under one roof," says Trump. "Well, it's probably the most expensive set of stores, certainly. And the greatest.\u000a\u000aAnd they're the most important stores." (Donald Trump's declarations have a habit of sliding up or down in magnitude. If he thinks he can get away with it, the statements become broader and more encompassing. When he has overstepped himself, he retrenches.) "People love Trump Tower because it's a scene, it's a talked-about scene. You know that people come from all over the world and say, 'We want to visit it.' It's become an attraction. All over the world they talk about this building. And they love it."\u000a\u000aEDITOR\u2019S PICK\u000a\u000aLast October, Trump paid Oklahoma oilman J. Walter Duncan about $6 million for the New Jersey Generals, one of eighteen teams in the fledgling United States Football League. The club, despite the presence of running back Herschel Walker, mustered a meager 6\u201312 record in a pretty meager league. "This football thing is crazy," says Trump. "I bought the team for very little money\u2014I paid much less than what is reported\u2014and we've created a value for it now. It's crazy what's happened."\u000a\u000aTrump kicked off his ownership with a hiring blitz. He got Gary Barbaro, the all-pro safety from Kansas City. Then he latched onto Dave Lapham, the veteran guard from the Bengals. Next, he wooed quarterback Brian Sipe away from the Browns with a two-year $1.9 million contract. Finally, he signed Bobby Leopold and Willie Harper from the 49ers. (To secure Walker from the NFL this spring, Trump gave his star back a four-year multimillion-dollar contract that Walker called "the best in the USFL and the National Football League.")\u000a\u000aWasting little time in clearing out the front office, Trump dumped coach Chuck Fairbanks and, after a widely reported courtship of Don Shula, hired former Jets coach Walt Michaels. Talks with Shula broke down, according to Trump, when the coach asked for the unaskable\u2014an apartment in Trump Tower. "That's something more valuable than money," said the owner at the time. "That's something I really consider gold." Shula recalls it differently: "All I did was listen to what he had to say. They approached me. I didn't approach them."\u000a\u000aThe staff scramble created a promotional windfall for Trump. During the winter, barely a day passed without a New York columnist trumpeting as an "exclusive" rumors of the new owner's latest acquisition. It could only have delighted Trump, who was enjoying a mano a mano publicity duel with New York's reigning sports baron, George Steinbrenner.\u000a\u000aHaving picked up the Generals for a relative song, Trump has kicked off his campaign for parity with the NFL, beginning with a little something he envisions as the "Galaxy Bowl," a play-off between the Super Bowl winner and the best team in the USFL. "I could have paid $40 or $50 million for an NFL team," says Trump. "I could have bought Baltimore. I could have bought a number of teams in the NFL. But I wanted a team in New York, and I couldn't buy the Giants or the Jets. Besides, it's more creative this way. In a couple of years, maybe the two leagues will be equal." (NFL Commissioner Pete Rozelle's reply is typically oblique: "The USFL has to do what's in its best interest.")\u000a\u000aTrump's first plan of attack is to change the playing season. "Right now," he says, "I like the concept of playing in the fall and winter, head-on against the NFL. The league is very vulnerable." Says USFL Commissioner Chet Simmons: "What we have in Don is an active young guy who is doing a lot of thinking, some of it off-the-cuff."\u000a\u000aThe press generated from Trump's wild plans seems to have paid off. He claims that the Generals have sold more than 30,000 season tickets. "People are hungry for a winning team in New York," says Trump. Earlier this year, Trump signed linebacker Lawrence Taylor to a playing contract that would begin once his contract with the Giants runs out in 1987. When the Giants decided they wanted Taylor's services beyond his present contract, they had to go to Trump. He charged them a $700,000 contract buy-out fee.\u000a\u000aTrump Tower is what its owner brazenly calls "the Tiffany location." "When you're in real estate," he says, "the expression 'Tiffany location' means the best." The folks next door, at Tiffany's, might reasonably argue that they, in fact, occupy the Tiffany location. But Trump didn't get to be what he is, or where he is, by acknowledging the competition. Where he is now, of course, is not so far geographically from where he started. Just walk a few blocks down Fifth from Trump Tower to the E train subway station and take it to the last stop on the line\u2014Jamaica Estates, Queens. This is where Trump grew up.\u000a\u000aTo smooth out his tendency to bulldoze those around him, he was carted off to the New York Military Academy at Cornwall-on-Hudson. "When I graduated," he recalls, "I was, like, the top-ranking guy in terms of the military. That doesn't mean I was able to get along with people, because the reason I went in the first place was that I didn't get along with a lot of people." Summers were spent doing errands for his father, Fred C. Trump, a former carpenter who had built a small empire of middle-class apartment buildings in Brooklyn, Queens, and Staten Island.\u000a\u000aFred Sr., now 78, still manages the family's rental units out of a modest office in a red brick building at 600 Avenue Z in the Coney Island section of Brooklyn. The office may be spare, but the bank account isn't. Forbes magazine has estimated Donald and his father's net worth to be in the $400 million bracket. Fred Jr., Donald's older brother, died of a heart ailment in 1981. One older sister, Maryanne Trump Barry, is a federal judge in New Jersey. The other, Elizabeth Trump, is an administrative assistant at Chase Manhattan, and his brother Robert, 34, is an executive vice-president of the Trump Organization.\u000a\u000a"It's magnificent," Trump says of his new Atlantic City hotel. "It's three blocks long, it's a megastructure. It's incredible. It's the largest casino in the world. It just dominates."\u000a\u000aWhile at the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School, Donald started putting together his first deals. "I began dabbling in real estate," he says, "buying brownstones, fixing them up a bit, and turning them over for a profit." In 1968 he joined the family-owned Trump Organization, by then landlord of 40,000 apartment units. It was all smalltime outer-borough stuff, though, and the newest member was busting to cross the East River into Manhattan. He'd already tested the waters once. "At one point, when I was very young," says Trump, "I was the producer of a Broadway play. Well, sort of a semiproducer. I helped raise money for a little show with Sam Levene and Molly Picon called Paris Is Out. I was only 22 years old. It's a crummy business."\u000a\u000aHe met Ivana Winkelmayr, his wife to be, at a party in New York, where the former Czech ski-team member was taking a break from her modeling career in Montreal. They were married within a year by the Trump family pastor, the Reverend Norman Vincent Peale. The influence of the latter may excuse Trump's showroom description of the former: "My wife was the number-one model in Montreal for eight years." Now cast in the mold of Leona Helmsley and Luba Potamkin, Ivana Trump has become a primo collaborator in her husband's endeavors, in charge of overseeing all the decorating details. She has helped design everything from the New Jersey Generals' cheerleaders' uniforms, to the commodes in Atlantic City, to the interior of their fifteen-bedroom Georgian manor house in Connecticut, to the lobby of Trump Tower. "We demolished a mountain of marble for Trump Tower," she boasts. "Twenty-five hundred tons. Then, believe it or not, one store tried to sneak Formica into their space and install nylon carpet instead of 100 percent wool."\u000a\u000aIn between meetings with contractors and designers at Trump Plaza and in Atlantic City, Ivana has been working on the triplex apartment atop Trump Tower, where the couple and their three children moved in March. "On the first floor here is the living room, dining room, kitchen, and entertainment rooms," she says. "The second floor has a balcony looking over the living room. On this floor is our bedroom, with a sitting room for us to watch a romantic movie or for Don to watch a football game. There are our bathrooms and our closets. And from the little bedroom on the second floor you can look down here into the living room, because everything is glass. It's a double-height living room. The third floor has the children's room and the maid's room, and the guest rooms. And then there is an elevator that services all three floors."\u000a\u000aAs in the movies, success in real estate often depends on the deal, and Trump, in his relatively short career, has proved himself a remarkably deft dealmaker. The Trump family's strong ties to the Brooklyn Democratic machine that launched the political careers of New York Governor Hugh Carey and New York Mayor Abe Beame haven't done Donald's career any harm either. "I got along with Carey," says Donald. "He was very good, and he was a good governor." Both Carey and Beame were in power in the mid-Seventies, when New York was facing bankruptcy and Trump made his first big deal\u2014a very complex one\u2014to build the Grand Hyatt Hotel. "The city was dead," says Donald. "As dead as it could be."\u000a\u000aEDITOR\u2019S PICK\u000a\u000aFor $500,000 he took an option on the Commodore Hotel, then owned by the Penn Central. When he heard that Hyatt was looking for a New York hotel site, he struck a partnership: Trump would build it on the land he had just leased, and Hyatt would manage it. With the help of George Peacock, now a senior vice-president of the Equitable Life Assurance Society, Trump rounded up tentative pledges for $70 million in mortgage money. "So I took this commitment, which was a statement with a hundred stipulations in it, to the city," Trump told The New York Times. "One of the conditions was that I would obtain a tax abatement. I told the city, I will build you this incredible, gorgeous, gleaming hotel. I will put people to work in the construction trades and save hotel jobs, and the Grand Central area, which was pretty depressing at the time, will come around. So the city made a deal."\u000a\u000aThrough an intricate financing package, Trump is now co-owner of the Grand Hyatt without having invested his own money. Then there is the abatement, which exempts the hotel from paying city taxes for the next forty years and is estimated to be worth $50 million. "Who knew that it would turn out as great as it did?" says Trump. "I didn't. I thought it could be fine, I thought it could be okay. And it's turned out to have the highest occupancy in New York. I don't know if you call that vision or luck. Perhaps it's a combination of both. It was all timing. In another year, I wouldn't have gotten the abatement."\u000a\u000aBut the Hyatt deal was just a warm-up for the main act, Trump Tower. A pattern would begin to develop. All of Trump's real estate projects are owned solely by himself and one major high ticket co-venturer. For Trump Tower it was again Equitable. "The Hyatt got us acquainted with Donald, and that led us to the next big one," says Peacock. An aide to Hugh Carey, Louise M. Sunshine (who is now, along with Ivana and Robert Trump, a Trump Organization executive vice-president), provided Donald with an introduction to David Evins, a major stockholder in Genesco, then the owner of Bonwit Teller. Conversation revealed that the cash-poor conglomerate might be willing to sell its lease on the building. Equitable owned the land under the building, and Tiffany's owned the air rights over it.\u000a\u000aChase financed the $24 million needed for all rights to the plot and then syndicated the entire $150 million construction loan. Trump sold the condominium apartments for $277 million. He and Equitable had split their first round of profits before any of the tenants had even moved in. "So we have about a $277 million sellout," says Trump, "just for the upper half of the building. And then we own the lower half for nothing." The partnership, unencumbered by mortgages, now collects the rents from thirteen floors of office space at $50 a square foot and the six levels of retail space at $150 to $450 a square foot. "It's a crazy deal," says Trump. "It's better than working."\u000a\u000aTrump's accomplishments have not been without cost both to the architectural heritage of the city and to the builder's own reputation. A lot of people just don't like Donald Trump very much. It probably started during the clean-up of Grand Central, when he hung an enormous banner over the side of the terminal with trump in big, bold letters. Destroying two bas-reliefs from the front of Bonwit Teller that had been promised to the Metropolitan Museum of Art did not further endear him to the public.\u000a\u000aTrump's version: "That's so overplayed, it's ridiculous. There was a good reason for doing that, which has not been explained well, with the insurance and the problems and the fact that it wasn't practical. We went through a whole zoning thing that lasted a year and a half, and nobody ever mentioned those two sculptures. Taking them down was very dangerous. If they broke, they would have fallen all over Fifth Avenue. They weren't even sculptures. They were stones with some engraving on them. They were nothing. Just junk."\u000a\u000aFrom the Metropolitan comes a slightly different view. "They were irreplaceable architectural documents," says Penelope Hunter-Stiebel, who handled the negotiations with Trump for the Met. "One of the friezes, a grillwork by Ely Jacques Kahn, was a textbook example of the 'moderne' style." Indeed, the "stones with some engraving on them" were appraised by Robert Miller of the Robert Miller Gallery at $250,000. Trump, says Miller, "is not an esthetic person."\u000a\u000aMore bad publicity followed Trump's tactics in trying to force out tenants from one of the apartment buildings he owns on Central Park South, maneuvers that included offering vacant apartments in the building to the homeless and covering up empty apartment windows and street-level storefronts with tin sheeting. Trump's version: "It's a building of a hundred rent-controlled units. There are multimillionaires living in the building\u2026or very wealthy people at least. Some pay as little as $300 or $400 a month. Actually, offering the apartments to the homeless wasn't such a good idea. In New York City, even if they don't have a lease, you can't get them out. It's the law. It's incredible. If I had put the homeless in there, I wouldn't have been able to get them out either. I'd have had to start the whole cycle over again. It's crazy."\u000a\u000aIt is nearing the end of winter, and young Donald's fancy turns to the two Trump projects nearing completion: the co-op on Manhattan's East Side and the hotel-casino in Atlantic City. But first, Donald wants to talk about the one that got away. "I offered to build the convention center [in New York City] for $250 million," says Trump. He also wanted to name it The Trump Convention Center, an appellation the city balked at. "It will now probably cost them over $450 million. Everybody had a site, you know, build it here, build it there, build it in Times Square. But ultimately they picked ours. The overruns aren't my fault. I got the land and got them to build on it and everything else. They blew it after that."\u000a\u000aConversely, Trump Plaza benefited from sheer promotional momentum. "I was watching the U.S. Open on television," Donald recalls, "when Martina Navratilova won. There were hundreds of photographers and reporters around her. She moved to the microphone, put down her trophy, and said something to the effect of, 'I thank you for the check. Now I'm going to buy an apartment at Trump Plaza in New York.' Now this is in a stadium filled with 20,000 people, on national television, international television, probably world television, and she said, 'I'm going to take this check and immediately run over and buy an apartment at Trump Plaza.'" And Navratilova did just that. So did Rawleigh Warner of Mobil Oil and former Kentucky governor John Y. Brown and his wife, Phyllis George. The $50 million cooperative development has also attracted a "lower echelon" of West Coast types on the order of Dick Clark, Chuck Barris, Norman Fell, and Regis Philbin. You get the idea.\u000a\u000aEDITOR\u2019S PICK\u000a\u000aOn an inspection tour of the building, Donald is all compliments. "Isn't that a great-looking elevator system? Gorgeous job, isn't it?" A saleswoman making the tour with him is herself a wellspring of enthusiasm. "The kitchens are small because most of our buyers are not that interested in cooking," she gushes. "They are people who, when they eat in, order intimate little dinner parties from The Silver Palate. And this over here is the third bedroom, which a lot of people use as a den because it's so well located. This room was designed by Angelo Donghia, who is kind of the doyen of everything!"\u000a\u000aTalk then turns to the deal in Atlantic City. Trump bought the land for the hotel cheap, before the referendum that brought gambling to the resort. The $250 million project, which looks like nothing less than two '58 Edsel grills placed together to form an inverted "T," should catch the weekend gambler's eye, even among the other garish monstrosities in Atlantic City. It certainly has caught Trump's. "I think it's going to be an incredible building," he says. "I think it's going to be the largest and one of the most spectacular hotels anywhere in the world. It's magnificent. It's three blocks long. It's a megastructure. It's incredible. It's the largest casino in the world. It just dominates."\u000a\u000aOn the way back to Trump Tower, the car glides by Central Park South. "I own the Barbizon Plaza. I own the whole block on Central Park South and Avenue of the Americas," says Donald, with a trace of exaggeration. (His two buildings probably comprise less than a sixth of the block.) "I could just leave the building standing and convert it to co-ops, but I don't want to do that, because it would be like a desecration of the Avenue of the Americas site." (Trump always calls Sixth Avenue, Avenue of the Americas. There is not a New Yorker alive who refers to the street by this name, except Trump. It probably sounds classier to deep-pocket Europeans.)\u000a\u000a"Right now I'm sort of assessing the alternatives," says Trump, who in the days ahead will announce expansive but tentative ideas for the future: plans for erecting the tallest building in the world, or putting together a deal for a giant domed stadium in the Bronx. "There are lots of crazy alternatives. A lot of things can happen. I don't know what is going to happen over the next ten years. I just couldn't predict. We've done a lot. I guess we've done as much as anybody in terms of business." Which reminds him: "Did you see that article on me in the business section of the [New York] Sunday Times?" (Had the visitor not seen it, he surely couldn't have missed the Lucite-framed copy that rests on the windowsill in Trump's office.) "That was the largest story the Times supposedly has ever done on the business page. It was big. Let's see\u2026it was half a front page, and a whole back page and some more. It was crazy. They tell me it was the longest story ever done on a person as a profile. They did a larger story on IBM. That was literally the largest, but it couldn't have been much longer. It was wild."\u000a\u000aAs the limo turns down Fifth Avenue, Trump motions about the car. "A coach-maker did this for me. It's wild, isn't it? We have the wet bar, the whole thing, the whole kaboodle. Look, it's got a TV and a radio." He leans forward to the driver. "Hey, Tony. You hear we just signed Freddie Gilbert, Herschel's friend from Georgia?" Before Tony can answer, Trump's mind is racing ahead to the view out the side window. "Did you ever pass Trump Tower at night and see the way it glows?" he asks. "It almost glows in the dark. That's because I used real bronze. If you get imitations, it doesn't look the same. It looks like nothing." He settles back into his seat. "I'm a first-class sort of person. I only go first class."
